1
00:01:22,958 --> 00:01:27,253
Blackberries!
I got blackberries!

2
00:01:43,270 --> 00:01:45,354
This'll be the last
of them now, Francie.

3
00:01:45,439 --> 00:01:48,107
Is that all, Mom?
Can we go now?

4
00:01:48,192 --> 00:01:50,401
Not so loud, Neeley.
Do you wanna wake
your papa up?

5
00:01:50,486 --> 00:01:53,196
Gosh, Francie,
ain't you through
with them dishes yet?

6
00:01:53,280 --> 00:01:55,740
She'll only be a minute.
My, I wish
you was as anxious

7
00:01:55,824 --> 00:01:58,451
to get going on
school mornings
as you is on Saturday.

8
00:01:58,535 --> 00:01:59,744
Papa was late
last night.

9
00:01:59,828 --> 00:02:01,829
Yeah, I was dead asleep
when he come in, I guess.

10
00:02:01,914 --> 00:02:04,707
He says if people
didn't like to make speeches
so much at dinners,

11
00:02:04,792 --> 00:02:06,626
waiters could
spend more time
with their families.

12
00:02:06,710 --> 00:02:08,544
It wasn't much
of a job, I guess.

13
00:02:08,629 --> 00:02:10,421
Them club dinners
don't tip much.

14
00:02:13,592 --> 00:02:14,675
Is that all, Mama?

15
00:02:14,760 --> 00:02:16,552
Yes, yes. Go on.
I'll dry 'em.

16
00:02:16,637 --> 00:02:18,346
You don't look like
you got much there
this week.

17
00:02:18,555 --> 00:02:19,597
One of these days,

18
00:02:19,681 --> 00:02:22,600
Mrs. Gaddis is gonna
throw away that old
wash boiler of hers.

19
00:02:22,684 --> 00:02:25,019
Carney will pay us plenty
for the copper bottom
off of that.

20
00:02:25,103 --> 00:02:26,979
He won't pay you any
more than he has to.

21
00:02:27,064 --> 00:02:29,315
You watch him on
that weighing, now.
Yes'm.

22
00:02:29,399 --> 00:02:33,486
Parents ought to have a day
that's like Saturday
is for kids. Go on.

23
00:02:33,570 --> 00:02:35,238
Maybe if I start
the lower hall

24
00:02:35,322 --> 00:02:36,447
and scrub
my way up today,

25
00:02:36,532 --> 00:02:38,491
it'll make
something special
out of it for me.

26
00:02:38,575 --> 00:02:40,368
Keep an eye
on him, Francie.
Come on!

27
00:02:40,452 --> 00:02:42,495
Yes, Mama!

28
00:02:42,579 --> 00:02:47,583
Rags! Old iron!
Rags! Old iron!

29
00:02:48,585 --> 00:02:51,212
Rags! Old iron!

30
00:03:03,100 --> 00:03:05,226
They done
good today.
Come on.

31
00:03:13,110 --> 00:03:16,863
Boarding!
89th Street!

32
00:03:17,573 --> 00:03:18,948
Neeley!

33
00:03:20,242 --> 00:03:24,036
Boarding!
89th Street!

34
00:03:24,288 --> 00:03:25,580
Ragpickers!

35
00:03:26,331 --> 00:03:27,623
Come on.

36
00:03:30,043 --> 00:03:33,671
Now, look. Stand on
the same side as him
when he weighs it

37
00:03:33,755 --> 00:03:35,047
so as he can reach it.

38
00:03:35,132 --> 00:03:38,092
And don't forget
to stand there
after he pays you.

39
00:03:38,176 --> 00:03:41,220
You forgot that last time,
and a penny's a penny,
ain't it?

40
00:03:41,305 --> 00:03:42,555
Well, I guess
I know it is.

41
00:03:42,639 --> 00:03:43,806
Well, all right, then.

42
00:03:48,478 --> 00:03:50,062
Three cents.
That stuff's worth
more than that.

43
00:03:50,147 --> 00:03:52,607
Shut up!
I say what things
are worth around here.

44
00:03:53,817 --> 00:03:55,359
Who's next?

45
00:03:56,653 --> 00:03:59,113
Hello, little girl.
Come on.

46
00:03:59,948 --> 00:04:01,699
Shut up!
Shut up!

47
00:04:15,047 --> 00:04:17,590
You done fine.
Nine cents.

48
00:04:20,594 --> 00:04:23,554
Three, five, nine.

49
00:04:26,850 --> 00:04:28,935
There you are,
an extra penny

50
00:04:29,019 --> 00:04:30,770
because you're a nice,
little girl.

51
00:04:31,563 --> 00:04:34,690
That's better.
I sure wish Carney
liked to pinch boys.

52
00:04:34,775 --> 00:04:36,525
Nine and my
pinching penny.

53
00:04:36,944 --> 00:04:38,945
Thirty-nine!
It's a pencil!

54
00:04:40,364 --> 00:04:42,073
Give me one.

55
00:04:47,079 --> 00:04:50,331
Twenty-six.
A pen wiper.

56
00:05:32,582 --> 00:05:33,874
Something you want,
little girl?

57
00:05:34,418 --> 00:05:36,669
I'm merely looking,
thank you.
I have a right.

58
00:05:36,753 --> 00:05:38,254
I have money.

59
00:05:41,800 --> 00:05:45,594
Step on a crack,
break your mother's back.

60
00:05:46,930 --> 00:05:48,597
Here she comes!
Cheese it!

61
00:06:00,610 --> 00:06:03,571
Neeley. Neeley,
we gotta go home!

62
00:06:03,655 --> 00:06:04,655
Beat it!

63
00:06:04,740 --> 00:06:05,698
Mama said.

64
00:06:05,782 --> 00:06:07,908
Mama said!
Mama said!

65
00:06:09,327 --> 00:06:10,453
I'll beat you!

66
00:06:10,537 --> 00:06:11,620
No, you won't!

67
00:06:13,081 --> 00:06:16,625
For heaven's sake.
Is it that late already?

68
00:06:17,502 --> 00:06:20,546
Well, I guess
I'll just let these
stairs go till later.

69
00:06:20,630 --> 00:06:22,506
Four cents, Mom.
That's pretty good.

70
00:06:22,591 --> 00:06:23,632
Dump the bucket, Neeley.

71
00:06:23,717 --> 00:06:24,717
Mama, can I...

72
00:06:24,801 --> 00:06:26,552
No. Dump the bucket
and bring it.

73
00:06:27,554 --> 00:06:30,139
Today's the day for
the insurance collector

74
00:06:30,223 --> 00:06:32,600
and I certainly don't
want him to catch me
looking like this.

75
00:06:32,684 --> 00:06:33,726
Hot, ain't it?

76
00:06:33,810 --> 00:06:35,895
Yeah, but Christmas
will be here
before you know it.

77
00:06:35,979 --> 00:06:38,481
I got enough troubles
without worrying about that.

78
00:06:38,565 --> 00:06:39,815
How's your sister
today, Henny?

79
00:06:39,941 --> 00:06:41,192
Poorly, thank you.

80
00:06:48,200 --> 00:06:49,825
Well, hello,
Flossie, dear.

81
00:06:50,494 --> 00:06:53,412
Hello, Mrs. Nolan.
Don't you notice
something?

82
00:06:53,497 --> 00:06:54,914
You look like you
was feeling better,

83
00:06:54,998 --> 00:06:56,582
much better.
Don't you, Francie?

84
00:06:56,666 --> 00:06:58,834
No, I don't!
I don't!

85
00:07:03,256 --> 00:07:05,091
Heat up the coffee
while I fix up.

86
00:07:06,927 --> 00:07:09,762
Right there.
That's better.

87
00:07:23,485 --> 00:07:25,361
Mom?
Yes, Neeley?

88
00:07:25,987 --> 00:07:28,906
Mom, if there was a rule
about something,

89
00:07:28,990 --> 00:07:31,367
that doesn't mean
you couldn't do something
else once in a while.

90
00:07:31,451 --> 00:07:35,121
Neeley, you cannot have
any of those pennies
to buy an ice cream cone.

91
00:07:35,205 --> 00:07:38,332
They go in the bank,
the same as usual.
Bring them in here, Neeley.

92
00:07:40,502 --> 00:07:42,378
Half of everything we get
goes into that bank.

93
00:07:42,462 --> 00:07:44,505
That's the way it is
and that's the way
it's gotta be, now.

94
00:07:44,589 --> 00:07:45,756
Put 'em in there.

95
00:07:45,841 --> 00:07:49,385
Gosh, I bet we got
about $100 in that
old bank by now.

96
00:07:49,553 --> 00:07:50,970
Nine's more like it.

97
00:07:52,889 --> 00:07:55,224
Mama! Mama,
they're cutting
the tree!

98
00:07:59,688 --> 00:08:01,730
Oh, that's too bad.

99
00:08:02,232 --> 00:08:05,651
It was kind of pretty there
with birds sitting
in it sometimes.

100
00:08:05,735 --> 00:08:07,236
Papa loved that tree.

101
00:08:07,737 --> 00:08:10,322
Quit mooning over it.
It got in the way
of the washing.

102
00:08:10,407 --> 00:08:12,658
A tree ain't gonna put
no pennies in the bank.

103
00:08:13,827 --> 00:08:14,952
It's Mr. Barker.

104
00:08:17,497 --> 00:08:19,748
Get out the good
cup and saucer
and give it a wipe.

105
00:08:19,833 --> 00:08:21,667
And, Francie,
you can stay
in the room,

106
00:08:21,751 --> 00:08:23,586
if you want,
while Mr. Barker's here.

107
00:08:25,797 --> 00:08:26,964
How do you do,
Mr. Barker?

108
00:08:27,048 --> 00:08:28,132
How do you do,
Francie?

109
00:08:28,216 --> 00:08:30,843
Mama is temporarily detained,
but will join you directly.

110
00:08:30,927 --> 00:08:32,344
Hello, Neeley.
Hello.

111
00:08:32,429 --> 00:08:35,014
Why, Francie,
you got manners
right out of a book.

112
00:08:35,098 --> 00:08:36,307
And company
or no company,

113
00:08:36,391 --> 00:08:38,100
Mrs. Nolan always
looks the lady.

114
00:08:38,935 --> 00:08:40,477
You should see
some of my people,

115
00:08:40,562 --> 00:08:42,479
even ladies with husbands
that work steady.

116
00:08:43,356 --> 00:08:45,482
Won't you go into the parlor
and have a cup of coffee?

117
00:08:45,567 --> 00:08:48,194
That, I will.
And your hospitality
is very kind, Mrs. Nolan.

118
00:08:49,154 --> 00:08:51,530
Well, old man Gentry's
off to jail again.

119
00:08:51,615 --> 00:08:52,990
That's too bad.

120
00:08:53,074 --> 00:08:55,117
But she's keeping up
his insurance
just the same.

121
00:08:55,202 --> 00:08:58,704
And here's ours.
Ten cents for me,
10 cents for Mr. Nolan,

122
00:08:58,788 --> 00:09:00,039
a nickel for each
of the children.

123
00:09:00,123 --> 00:09:01,874
And you'll never
regret it, Mrs. Nolan.

124
00:09:01,958 --> 00:09:04,960
A fine funeral
for every member of
the family, heaven forbid.

125
00:09:05,462 --> 00:09:07,213
And now
your weekly receipts,
Mrs. Nolan.

126
00:09:07,797 --> 00:09:09,465
Now there's one party
not far from here,

127
00:09:09,549 --> 00:09:12,509
I wouldn't like to say who,
that didn't get no receipts
this week.

128
00:09:13,220 --> 00:09:14,803
And naming no names,
I will say

129
00:09:14,888 --> 00:09:16,305
that it's a family
that the angel of death

130
00:09:16,389 --> 00:09:18,891
has marked on
his invitation list.
Heaven forbid.

131
00:09:18,975 --> 00:09:21,435
Henny says his sister's
got one foot in the grave.

132
00:09:21,978 --> 00:09:23,437
Neeley!

133
00:09:23,521 --> 00:09:24,897
It'll mean
Potter's Field,
most likely.

134
00:09:24,981 --> 00:09:26,148
Thank you, Francie.

135
00:09:26,316 --> 00:09:27,858
Well, that's
what people get.

136
00:09:28,401 --> 00:09:30,903
Wasting good money
to give her dresses
instead of insurance.

137
00:09:30,987 --> 00:09:32,863
Dresses that'll last
longer than she will.

138
00:09:33,281 --> 00:09:35,282
All depends on
what folks thinks
is important.

139
00:09:35,367 --> 00:09:36,492
Papa says dresses...

140
00:09:36,576 --> 00:09:37,660
That's right,
Mr. Barker.

141
00:09:37,744 --> 00:09:40,120
It all depends on
what folks thinks
is important.

142
00:09:40,997 --> 00:09:44,458
And how is Mr. Nolan?
Is he working
or not working?

143
00:09:44,542 --> 00:09:47,670
Some tell me one thing,
some another.
Of course, I don't listen.

144
00:09:48,546 --> 00:09:50,589
Mr. Nolan,
being a singing waiter,
Mr. Barker,

145
00:09:50,674 --> 00:09:51,840
and what you might
call an artist,

146
00:09:51,925 --> 00:09:54,176
his work don't come steady
like other people's.

147
00:09:54,636 --> 00:09:56,762
But I'm sure
you'll remember when
you talk to folks

148
00:09:56,846 --> 00:09:59,348
that the Nolans
have always paid
their insurance on the dot.

149
00:09:59,432 --> 00:10:01,058
You surely don't
think I go around

150
00:10:01,142 --> 00:10:03,102
spreading gossip
about my clients,
Mrs. Nolan.

151
00:10:03,186 --> 00:10:05,938
Sure not.
And how's my mother,
Mr. Barker?

152
00:10:06,398 --> 00:10:08,941
In the prime,
Mrs. Nolan.
Fine as can be.

153
00:10:09,025 --> 00:10:10,693
And she says
to tell you
she'll be over...

154
00:10:11,361 --> 00:10:13,779
Over tonight,
same as usual.

155
00:10:14,531 --> 00:10:18,242
And I trust
you're pleased with
the news about your sister.

156
00:10:19,035 --> 00:10:21,620
Just which news
do you mean,
Mr. Barker?

157
00:10:22,414 --> 00:10:24,581
Well, now,
she must be saving it to
surprise you with tonight

158
00:10:24,666 --> 00:10:26,166
when the family's
all here together.

159
00:10:26,710 --> 00:10:29,003
I'd take it kindly
if you told me
what you mean.

160
00:10:29,379 --> 00:10:33,173
Well, I trot around,
same as usual,
to collect her weekly dime

161
00:10:33,258 --> 00:10:34,675
and what do you
think happens?

162
00:10:34,843 --> 00:10:36,927
Well, sir,
she gives me
two dimes.

163
00:10:37,637 --> 00:10:39,471
Yes, sir,
she's done it again.

164
00:10:39,556 --> 00:10:41,724
She's got herself
a brand-new husband.

165
00:10:41,808 --> 00:10:43,142
Oh, no!

166
00:10:43,226 --> 00:10:45,686
Well, now, I suppose
you mean about her
still being married.

167
00:10:45,979 --> 00:10:48,063
I don't mind saying
I had the same
thought myself.

168
00:10:48,481 --> 00:10:50,065
But I'm sure
it must be all right.

169
00:10:50,150 --> 00:10:52,192
She must have made
some arrangement.

170
00:10:52,777 --> 00:10:54,320
I'm quite sure she did,
Mr. Barker.

171
00:10:54,404 --> 00:10:56,572
Does she call
this one Bill, too?

172
00:10:57,407 --> 00:10:59,408
You children run along now
and do the marketing.

173
00:10:59,492 --> 00:11:01,493
Go on.
Take some money
from the cup

174
00:11:01,578 --> 00:11:04,580
and get
a five-cent soup bone
off of Hassler's.

175
00:11:04,664 --> 00:11:06,332
Don't get the chopped meat
from him, though.

176
00:11:06,416 --> 00:11:09,043
He grinds it
behind closed doors
and heaven only knows.

177
00:11:09,127 --> 00:11:10,502
Go to Werner's
for the meat.

178
00:11:10,587 --> 00:11:13,172
Ask for round steak,
chopped, 10 cents' worth.

179
00:11:13,256 --> 00:11:15,007
And don't let him
give it to you
off the plate.

180
00:11:15,091 --> 00:11:17,760
Take an onion, Neeley!
And ask him to chop it in.

181
00:11:17,844 --> 00:11:21,013
And then just at the last,
ask for a piece of suet
to fry it with.

182
00:11:21,097 --> 00:11:22,556
But he won't always
do that, Mama.

183
00:11:22,640 --> 00:11:24,058
Tell him
your mama said.

184
00:11:24,142 --> 00:11:25,225
And then go
for the bread.

185
00:11:25,310 --> 00:11:26,352
It's Saturday, Mom.

186
00:11:26,436 --> 00:11:28,437
All right.
Ask for a nice pie,
not too crushed.

187
00:11:28,521 --> 00:11:30,064
Now, go on.
But, Mama, we know

188
00:11:30,148 --> 00:11:31,690
Aunt Sissy's been
married before.

189
00:11:31,775 --> 00:11:33,692
Sure. I can remember
two Uncle Bills.

190
00:11:33,777 --> 00:11:35,027
That's nothing for
you to talk about.

191
00:11:35,111 --> 00:11:36,945
Now run along now
and get things done.

192
00:11:43,119 --> 00:11:46,038
You got no right, Mr. Barker,
to be carrying tales
about my sister

193
00:11:46,122 --> 00:11:47,873
as though there were
something wrong.

194
00:11:47,957 --> 00:11:52,336
She may be funny some ways,
but she wouldn't do
nothing wrong,

195
00:11:52,420 --> 00:11:55,214
so I'd like it
if you didn't talk to
people like it was.

196
00:11:55,298 --> 00:11:57,674
Strike me dead
if I'd ever think of
mentioning it to anyone

197
00:11:57,759 --> 00:11:58,884
but you, Mrs. Nolan.

198
00:11:58,968 --> 00:12:00,010
Yeah, sure. I know.

199
00:12:01,137 --> 00:12:04,973
Well, you might
as well go on now
and tell me what you do know.

200
00:12:05,308 --> 00:12:07,893
No point in my being
the only one
who don't hear it.

201
00:12:08,269 --> 00:12:09,269
Well...

202
00:12:09,562 --> 00:12:11,563
Ten cents' worth
of round steak?
You want it ground?

203
00:12:11,648 --> 00:12:13,190
No, thank you.
You're sure now?

204
00:12:13,274 --> 00:12:15,734
It wasn't 20 minutes ago
I ground that
whole plateful fresh.

205
00:12:15,819 --> 00:12:16,985
No, thank you.

206
00:12:25,703 --> 00:12:27,955
Oh, I forgot.
My mama wants it ground.

207
00:12:29,457 --> 00:12:30,666
You don't tell me.

208
00:12:32,001 --> 00:12:33,836
And she said to
chop that in with it.

209
00:12:34,462 --> 00:12:35,796
She did?

210
00:12:43,763 --> 00:12:46,014
And a piece of suet
to fry it with,
Mama said.

211
00:12:46,391 --> 00:12:49,143
Sweet jumping
Christopher!

212
00:12:53,022 --> 00:12:55,941
Olives!
Sweet potatoes!

213
00:12:58,611 --> 00:13:01,280
You know, Mama thinks
we don't know anything.

214
00:13:01,364 --> 00:13:03,657
Yeah. She acts
like we were kids
or something.

215
00:13:04,033 --> 00:13:06,577
I bet she has a fight
with Aunt Sissy tonight.

216
00:13:06,661 --> 00:13:09,371
It's got
something to do with men
like Aunt Sissy too much.

217
00:13:09,456 --> 00:13:12,291
But Papa says
we ought to make
everybody like us.

218
00:13:12,375 --> 00:13:14,293
I guess maybe
ladies shouldn't.

219
00:13:14,377 --> 00:13:16,462
Maybe Aunt Sissy
wouldn't have changed
husbands so much

220
00:13:16,546 --> 00:13:18,297
if any of her babies
would've lived.

221
00:13:18,381 --> 00:13:20,048
She's crazy
about babies.

222
00:13:20,133 --> 00:13:23,135
Look who's talking
about babies.
A lot you know.

223
00:13:23,219 --> 00:13:24,428
I know as much
as you do.

224
00:13:24,512 --> 00:13:25,637
You don't know nothing.

225
00:13:25,722 --> 00:13:28,348
You think you're so smart.
Boys make me sick!

226
00:13:28,433 --> 00:13:29,683
What do you think
girls make people?

227
00:13:29,767 --> 00:13:30,976
Here she comes!

228
00:13:31,936 --> 00:13:33,645
Come on!

229
00:13:43,740 --> 00:13:45,908
Mister,
give us a white bread.

230
00:13:46,743 --> 00:13:47,993
Six loaves!

231
00:13:48,077 --> 00:13:49,620
And a pie,
not too crushed!

232
00:13:52,332 --> 00:13:53,707
This bread's fine.
I wouldn't be surprised

233
00:13:53,791 --> 00:13:55,167
if wasn't more
than three days old.

234
00:13:55,251 --> 00:13:56,752
Is that all, Mom?
Can we go now?

235
00:13:56,836 --> 00:13:58,003
Yes, you're free.

236
00:14:03,801 --> 00:14:04,843
Where's the fire?

237
00:14:04,928 --> 00:14:06,178
There's a scout for
the Brooklyns around.

238
00:14:06,262 --> 00:14:07,804
They're looking
for a catcher.

239
00:14:08,181 --> 00:14:10,057
Where are you going?
No place much.

240
00:14:10,141 --> 00:14:12,267
Well, don't go
dream walking
crossing the street.

241
00:14:26,616 --> 00:14:27,991
"Browning."

242
00:14:28,785 --> 00:14:30,953
"B-U... Burton."

243
00:14:32,038 --> 00:14:33,580
Anatomy of Melancholy.

244
00:14:47,053 --> 00:14:49,846
Burton's
Anatomy of Melancholy.

245
00:14:59,899 --> 00:15:02,025
Burton's
Anatomy of Melancholy?

246
00:15:02,443 --> 00:15:03,443
Are you sure
you want this?

247
00:15:03,528 --> 00:15:04,528
Yes, ma'am.

248
00:15:04,612 --> 00:15:06,238
Don't you think
it's a trifle
over your head?

249
00:15:06,322 --> 00:15:07,447
Yes, ma'am.

250
00:15:07,532 --> 00:15:08,657
Well, then,
why did you select it?

251
00:15:09,576 --> 00:15:13,412
Well,
I've read all the authors
beginning with "A"

252
00:15:13,496 --> 00:15:16,373
and all the "B's"
down to Burton.
It's next.

253
00:15:16,457 --> 00:15:19,418
You mean you're trying
to read your way straight
through the library?

254
00:15:19,711 --> 00:15:20,711
Yes, ma'am.

255
00:15:20,795 --> 00:15:22,254
But a book like this,
you'll only be confused.

256
00:15:22,338 --> 00:15:24,840
Please.
I wanna read clear
through the alphabet.

257
00:15:24,924 --> 00:15:27,009
I want to know
everything in the world.

258
00:15:27,844 --> 00:15:29,136
Well...

259
00:15:31,180 --> 00:15:34,808
All right.
Only do something
for me, will you?

260
00:15:35,393 --> 00:15:37,561
Take another book,
too. Here.

261
00:15:37,645 --> 00:15:40,606
When Knighthood
Was in Flower,
just for fun.

262
00:15:40,690 --> 00:15:43,609
It's Saturday.
I'll have a headache
thinking about you

263
00:15:43,693 --> 00:15:46,528
wrestling with
The Anatomy of Melancholy
all weekend.

264
00:15:47,280 --> 00:15:48,447
Will you?

265
00:15:49,032 --> 00:15:50,240
Yes, ma'am.

266
00:16:01,669 --> 00:16:03,754
A little more to the left,
Mr. Crackenbox!

267
00:16:03,838 --> 00:16:05,797
You think I want
Mrs. Whittely's
baby clothes?

268
00:16:05,882 --> 00:16:07,591
It's your wash,
your baby.

269
00:16:07,717 --> 00:16:09,426
Don't forget
to fix mine,
Mr. Crackenbox!

270
00:16:11,220 --> 00:16:13,722
Maybe you'd like
to come up here
and fix it yourselves

271
00:16:13,806 --> 00:16:16,725
and that's just
what you'll be doing
if you don't shut up!

272
00:16:26,569 --> 00:16:30,238
Mr. Crackenbox,
it still sags!

273
00:16:31,240 --> 00:16:35,410
Now, Mr. Crackenbox,
get it just a little bit
higher, if you don't mind.

274
00:16:40,541 --> 00:16:42,417
...her wheelbarrow

275
00:16:42,543 --> 00:16:44,753
Through streets broad
and narrow

276
00:16:45,213 --> 00:16:49,299
Crying cockles and mussels,
alive, alive-O

277
00:16:49,384 --> 00:16:50,342
I won, I won!

278
00:16:50,426 --> 00:16:52,344
Well, now,
I wouldn't be too sure
about that if I was you.

279
00:16:52,428 --> 00:16:54,763
But I did! I got it open
before you finished
and that's the rules.

280
00:16:54,847 --> 00:16:57,140
But I came up one flight
two steps at a time
before I remembered.

281
00:16:57,225 --> 00:16:58,183
Don't that make
a difference?

282
00:16:58,267 --> 00:16:59,309
No, sir.
The rules...

283
00:16:59,394 --> 00:17:01,186
And in a manner of speaking,
you never did stop me at all

284
00:17:01,270 --> 00:17:02,813
because my heart kept
right on singing.

285
00:17:03,356 --> 00:17:04,523
Papa, you're joking.

286
00:17:04,607 --> 00:17:05,941
Well, I guess
I'll let you get away

287
00:17:06,025 --> 00:17:07,401
with winning this time,
prima donna.

288
00:17:07,527 --> 00:17:09,444
And where's your
beautiful mama?
Finishing the hall.

289
00:17:09,529 --> 00:17:11,363
She must be on the top floor
or she'd have heard you.

290
00:17:11,447 --> 00:17:13,824
Well, in that case,
why ain't you
getting busy?

291
00:17:13,908 --> 00:17:15,450
Why ain't you
laying out my clothes?

292
00:17:15,535 --> 00:17:17,202
Papa,
you always make fun.

293
00:17:17,286 --> 00:17:18,870
You know you haven't
any more clothes.

294
00:17:18,955 --> 00:17:20,497
Haven't any
more clothes?

295
00:17:20,581 --> 00:17:22,124
What's this?
A tie.

296
00:17:22,208 --> 00:17:24,334
And this? And this?
A dickey. An apron.

297
00:17:24,419 --> 00:17:27,212
Them's clothes, ain't they?
And you'd better be getting
that apron ironed, too.

298
00:17:27,296 --> 00:17:28,880
Papa, you got a job
for tonight?

299
00:17:28,965 --> 00:17:30,173
You see the palm
of that hand?

300
00:17:30,258 --> 00:17:31,633
That's right where
I got the world tonight.

301
00:17:31,718 --> 00:17:32,759
Where's the job, Papa?

302
00:17:32,844 --> 00:17:34,594
Klommer's.
A big wedding party.

303
00:17:34,679 --> 00:17:37,055
And you know something,
prima donna?
There'll be plenty of tips.

304
00:17:37,140 --> 00:17:38,682
Singing or waiting?
Both.

305
00:17:38,766 --> 00:17:40,392
Maybe tonight will be it.

306
00:17:40,476 --> 00:17:43,145
Maybe tonight
he'll be there,
the impresario.

307
00:17:43,229 --> 00:17:45,397
And he'll hear you sing,
and he'll put you
on the stage.

308
00:17:45,481 --> 00:17:47,399
And why not?
Ain't I the Brooklyn Thrush?

309
00:17:47,483 --> 00:17:49,568
Papa!

310
00:17:49,652 --> 00:17:51,903
And now you'd better be
getting my apron ironed.

311
00:17:51,988 --> 00:17:54,239
Have it in a jiffy, Papa.
The coffee's on.

312
00:17:54,323 --> 00:17:55,657
That's my prima donna.

313
00:17:56,325 --> 00:17:59,828
Early one morning
I heard a maiden singing

314
00:18:03,332 --> 00:18:05,417
Oh, Papa, I can't sing.

315
00:18:05,501 --> 00:18:07,544
Come on, now.
You're holding up
the singing.

316
00:18:07,670 --> 00:18:11,882
Oh, don't deceive me
Oh, never leave me

317
00:18:12,175 --> 00:18:14,134
And better singing
I never did hear.

318
00:18:14,552 --> 00:18:16,178
I love to iron
for you, Papa.

319
00:18:16,262 --> 00:18:18,180
You know something,
a day like this

320
00:18:18,264 --> 00:18:19,931
is just like somebody
gave you a present.

321
00:18:20,016 --> 00:18:21,516
Everything just right.

322
00:18:22,685 --> 00:18:24,853
I wonder what people did
before they invented coffee.

323
00:18:26,022 --> 00:18:28,356
This sure could be
a fine world if...

324
00:18:30,568 --> 00:18:32,611
Hey, you know something,
prima donna?

325
00:18:32,695 --> 00:18:34,946
You're going to make
somebody a mighty
fine wife someday.

326
00:18:35,031 --> 00:18:36,072
Papa!

327
00:18:36,157 --> 00:18:40,368
And very pretty, too.
That is, if your nose
doesn't grow crooked.

328
00:18:40,995 --> 00:18:43,205
Could it really?
Honest?

329
00:18:44,207 --> 00:18:46,625
No.
It's the prettiest nose
in all Brooklyn.

330
00:18:46,709 --> 00:18:48,001
Papa, it isn't.

331
00:18:48,085 --> 00:18:49,127
Who says it isn't?

332
00:18:49,212 --> 00:18:51,129
You just tell me who said it
and I'll take care of him.

333
00:18:51,714 --> 00:18:53,799
Papa, you're crazy.
And you know
something else?

334
00:18:53,883 --> 00:18:56,760
You're not gonna be
ironing like this when
that impresario comes along.

335
00:18:56,844 --> 00:18:58,845
Things are gonna be
different around here.
You wait and see.

336
00:18:58,930 --> 00:19:00,222
Yes, Papa.
Hey.

337
00:19:00,306 --> 00:19:01,598
What's the wish
you wish the most

338
00:19:01,682 --> 00:19:03,016
when our ship
comes sailing in?

339
00:19:03,476 --> 00:19:05,101
Well, it already
came true.

340
00:19:05,186 --> 00:19:06,728
What is it?
Come on and tell me.

341
00:19:07,522 --> 00:19:10,398
Well, I wished that when
you came home today

342
00:19:10,858 --> 00:19:12,734
you wouldn't be sick.

343
00:19:17,573 --> 00:19:19,908
Who told you to
call it "sick," baby?

344
00:19:20,284 --> 00:19:23,161
You shouldn't
waste your wishes
on things like that.

345
00:19:23,246 --> 00:19:26,873
You should be saving them
for a silk dress
or something.

346
00:19:27,625 --> 00:19:29,376
Haven't you got
a better wish
than that?

347
00:19:29,669 --> 00:19:31,586
Well...
Come on.

348
00:19:31,671 --> 00:19:34,506
Well, I hope Mama won't be
too mad with Aunt Sissy.

349
00:19:34,841 --> 00:19:36,299
What about Aunt Sissy?

350
00:19:36,384 --> 00:19:40,262
She's gone and got herself
another husband again.

351
00:19:40,429 --> 00:19:42,597
No!

352
00:19:42,682 --> 00:19:45,934
No! Gee, if there
isn't a woman for you.

353
00:19:46,018 --> 00:19:48,144
Hey. What did
your mama say?

354
00:19:48,229 --> 00:19:49,604
Well,
she didn't like it.

355
00:19:49,689 --> 00:19:51,189
Yeah.
I can imagine that.

356
00:19:52,441 --> 00:19:54,359
Couldn't you sort of
say something to her,

357
00:19:54,443 --> 00:19:56,319
not to be too mad
to Aunt Sissy?

358
00:19:57,029 --> 00:19:58,738
That I could,
prima donna,
and that I will.

359
00:19:58,823 --> 00:20:00,407
Thank you, Papa.

360
00:20:00,741 --> 00:20:03,577
Now, haven't you got
just one little wish
for yourself?

361
00:20:04,704 --> 00:20:07,205
Just one wish
just for you?

362
00:20:08,416 --> 00:20:11,710
Well, did you
see it, Papa?
What?

363
00:20:11,794 --> 00:20:14,921
Out the window,
our tree,
they've killed it!

364
00:20:18,926 --> 00:20:21,845
Well, will you
look at that, now?

365
00:20:21,929 --> 00:20:24,639
They didn't have
any right to kill it,
did they, Papa?

366
00:20:26,225 --> 00:20:28,894
Now, wait a minute.
They didn't kill it.

367
00:20:29,020 --> 00:20:31,605
Why, they couldn't
kill that tree.
Honest?

368
00:20:31,689 --> 00:20:33,231
Why, sure, baby.

369
00:20:33,316 --> 00:20:35,817
Don't tell me
that tree's gonna lay down
and die that easy.

370
00:20:36,986 --> 00:20:39,237
Look at that tree.
See where
it's coming from?

371
00:20:39,322 --> 00:20:40,655
Right up
out of the cement.

372
00:20:41,240 --> 00:20:44,910
Didn't nobody plant it.
It didn't ask
the cement could it grow.

373
00:20:44,994 --> 00:20:46,369
It just couldn't help
growing so much,

374
00:20:46,454 --> 00:20:48,121
it pushed that old cement
right out of the way.

375
00:20:48,205 --> 00:20:50,707
But when you're busting
with something like that,
can't anybody help it.

376
00:20:51,834 --> 00:20:56,504
Like, like that
little old bird up there.
Listen to him.

377
00:21:01,010 --> 00:21:02,719
He didn't ask anybody
could he sing.

378
00:21:02,803 --> 00:21:04,846
And he certainly
didn't take any lessons.

379
00:21:04,931 --> 00:21:07,974
He's so full of singing
it's just got to
bust out someplace.

380
00:21:08,059 --> 00:21:10,602
Why, they could
cut that old tree
right down to the ground

381
00:21:10,686 --> 00:21:13,063
and a root would push up
someplace else in the cement.

382
00:21:13,147 --> 00:21:15,190
You wait till spring,
prima donna,
and you'll see.

383
00:21:17,151 --> 00:21:20,028
Well, this ain't winning
the family bread, huh?

384
00:21:22,865 --> 00:21:26,743
Come on. Ain't you got
one nice, little wish
just for yourself?

385
00:21:28,120 --> 00:21:31,665
No, Papa. I just...

386
00:21:31,749 --> 00:21:33,458
Just what?

387
00:21:33,542 --> 00:21:35,794
I just love you
so much, Papa!

388
00:21:37,964 --> 00:21:41,174
Well, what do you know?

389
00:21:42,969 --> 00:21:44,135
Listen.

390
00:21:44,762 --> 00:21:47,681
If I make a lot of
tips tonight, you know
what I'm gonna do?

391
00:21:48,599 --> 00:21:50,016
What, Papa?

392
00:21:50,101 --> 00:21:53,186
I'm gonna put two bucks
on the nose of a horse
I know is running Monday.

393
00:21:53,980 --> 00:21:56,898
And I'll win 10.
Then I'll put it
on another horse.

394
00:21:56,983 --> 00:21:58,984
If I use my head
and I'm lucky,

395
00:21:59,068 --> 00:22:00,902
I'll run it up
to 500 bucks.

396
00:22:01,904 --> 00:22:03,738
Then you know
what I'm gonna do?
What, Papa?

397
00:22:04,740 --> 00:22:07,075
I'm gonna
take you on a trip,

398
00:22:07,159 --> 00:22:10,078
just you and me
on a regular train.

399
00:22:11,455 --> 00:22:13,289
Maybe we'll go down south
and see the cotton.

400
00:22:13,874 --> 00:22:16,376
You know,
down where them
cotton blossoms blow.

401
00:22:17,128 --> 00:22:20,588
Way down
upon the Swanee River

402
00:22:20,923 --> 00:22:23,341
Far, far away

403
00:22:25,428 --> 00:22:26,636
You're a nice girl, baby.

404
00:22:27,096 --> 00:22:29,889
Come on! We'll go up
and tell your mama
the news about my job!

405
00:22:36,480 --> 00:22:38,606
Anybody seen
Johnny Nolan's wife?

406
00:22:38,941 --> 00:22:42,527
Johnny, you all right?
And why not?

407
00:22:42,611 --> 00:22:44,279
Ain't I married to
the most beautiful lady

408
00:22:44,363 --> 00:22:46,406
in all Williamsburg,
Brooklyn?

409
00:22:46,490 --> 00:22:47,949
Well, you're shouting
it so loud

410
00:22:48,034 --> 00:22:49,367
they'll hear you
over to Manhattan.

411
00:22:49,452 --> 00:22:51,327
Don't you get fresh
with me tonight,
Mrs. Nolan.

412
00:22:51,412 --> 00:22:53,204
Happens I'm working Klommer's
big wedding party.

413
00:22:53,289 --> 00:22:55,331
I thought you looked
kinda extra dressy.

414
00:22:55,416 --> 00:22:57,208
I guess you won't get home
until the sun comes up.

415
00:22:57,293 --> 00:22:58,543
The later, the better.
The more tips,

416
00:22:58,627 --> 00:23:01,212
the more fine silk stockings
for my wife's pretty legs.

417
00:23:01,297 --> 00:23:03,298
Silk stockings is
just what I need!

418
00:23:03,716 --> 00:23:05,133
Now, just a minute,
Mrs. Nolan.

419
00:23:05,217 --> 00:23:06,468
Ain't you gonna give me
a kiss for luck?

420
00:23:06,552 --> 00:23:07,927
The whole house
is looking.

421
00:23:08,012 --> 00:23:10,180
Sure. I know
they're looking,
but who cares?

422
00:23:10,264 --> 00:23:11,723
This is the finest job
I had in months.

423
00:23:11,807 --> 00:23:13,099
Maybe I'll get
more from tonight.

424
00:23:13,184 --> 00:23:15,727
You better get on with it.
Good jobs don't wait.

425
00:23:15,811 --> 00:23:17,979
But the job's no good
without you. Kiss me.

426
00:23:24,153 --> 00:23:26,988
Well, you still
got a way with you,
Johnny Nolan.

427
00:23:27,073 --> 00:23:29,074
Now, go on!
Get out of here!

428
00:23:29,158 --> 00:23:30,575
Before you know it,
the folks at that wedding

429
00:23:30,659 --> 00:23:32,077
will be an old,
married couple.

430
00:23:32,161 --> 00:23:33,745
Before you know it,
I won't go at all.

431
00:23:33,829 --> 00:23:35,371
Theirs ain't the only
marriage that counts.

432
00:23:35,456 --> 00:23:36,581
Take your hat
and get out of here

433
00:23:36,665 --> 00:23:38,583
before someone else
cops that job!

434
00:23:39,835 --> 00:23:43,880
Our Francie was
telling me that

435
00:23:43,964 --> 00:23:46,174
Sissy's gone
and done it again.

436
00:23:47,968 --> 00:23:49,844
Well, maybe
he's a nice fella.

437
00:23:50,387 --> 00:23:52,305
Don't be too hard
on her, huh?

438
00:23:52,389 --> 00:23:55,141
They was all nice fellas.
Beat it, now, Johnny.

439
00:23:56,060 --> 00:23:57,936
That's just a sample, madam.

440
00:23:58,020 --> 00:23:59,646
If you like my stock,
drop me a card

441
00:23:59,730 --> 00:24:02,148
and I'll be back again.
Good evening.

442
00:24:06,028 --> 00:24:10,698
Well, will you look
at our beautiful
princess tonight

443
00:24:11,784 --> 00:24:13,451
in a brand-new gown.

444
00:24:13,536 --> 00:24:14,869
It's made out of silk.

445
00:24:14,954 --> 00:24:15,954
Silk?

446
00:24:16,205 --> 00:24:18,123
Don't you tell me that.

447
00:24:18,207 --> 00:24:21,251
This dress is made
out of flower petals
and birds' wings

448
00:24:21,961 --> 00:24:23,837
and a little old
piece of cloud.

449
00:24:25,589 --> 00:24:27,006
Anybody can tell that.

450
00:24:30,594 --> 00:24:31,636
Good evening,
Mr. Spencer.

451
00:24:31,720 --> 00:24:32,762
Working tonight,
Johnny?

452
00:24:32,847 --> 00:24:34,472
Yeah. Big wedding party.

453
00:24:34,557 --> 00:24:36,766
Good evening,
Miss Lizzie, Miss Maggie.

454
00:24:36,892 --> 00:24:39,102
You're looking fine
today, Mr. Nolan.
Indeed, you are.

455
00:24:39,186 --> 00:24:40,311
Thank you, ladies.

456
00:24:40,396 --> 00:24:42,438
Here comes the bride
Here...

457
00:24:42,565 --> 00:24:44,482
Good evening,
young ladies.
Good evening.

458
00:24:44,567 --> 00:24:45,692
Allow me, princess.

459
00:24:45,776 --> 00:24:47,277
Blackberries!

460
00:24:47,361 --> 00:24:49,863
I got blackberries!

461
00:24:51,031 --> 00:24:53,032
Hi, Mr. Ching.
Hello.

462
00:24:53,117 --> 00:24:55,869
What did Mama say
about Aunt Sissy?
Now don't worry about it.

463
00:24:55,953 --> 00:24:57,245
Everything's
gonna be all right.

464
00:24:57,329 --> 00:24:59,539
Your Aunt Sissy's
a fine woman, Francie.

465
00:25:01,041 --> 00:25:02,417
Look at them things!

466
00:25:05,880 --> 00:25:08,590
There's no use talking.
Someday I'm gonna
buy you them skates.

467
00:25:08,674 --> 00:25:10,508
Mama says not to be
too late, Papa.

468
00:25:10,593 --> 00:25:12,468
Look.
God invented time.

469
00:25:12,553 --> 00:25:15,013
And when he invents something,
there's always plenty of it.

470
00:25:15,097 --> 00:25:16,389
There's your car, Papa.

471
00:25:16,473 --> 00:25:18,099
Boy!
Look at them knives!

472
00:25:18,267 --> 00:25:19,851
Mama says
time is money.

473
00:25:19,935 --> 00:25:22,687
I guess he wasn't
worrying much about
money right then.

474
00:25:22,771 --> 00:25:24,480
There's your car, Papa.

475
00:25:24,607 --> 00:25:26,357
Well, I might
as well catch it.

476
00:25:38,913 --> 00:25:43,166
Ice! Any ice today?

477
00:25:44,627 --> 00:25:45,877
Supper's ready.

478
00:25:45,961 --> 00:25:47,128
Hey. Am I hungry!

479
00:25:47,254 --> 00:25:49,088
And when
weren't you hungry?
Mama?

480
00:25:49,173 --> 00:25:50,215
Yes, Francie?

481
00:25:50,299 --> 00:25:51,341
What does white mean?

482
00:25:51,425 --> 00:25:54,677
Just white, I guess.
What do you mean
what does it mean?

483
00:25:54,762 --> 00:25:56,429
Neeley, sit down
at your place.

484
00:25:56,513 --> 00:25:58,264
Why do girls always wear it
when they're married

485
00:25:58,349 --> 00:26:00,433
and when they're confirmed
and when they graduate?

486
00:26:00,517 --> 00:26:02,477
Why does it always
have to be white?

487
00:26:02,645 --> 00:26:05,647
Just one of those things
somebody started.
Lots of things like that.

488
00:26:05,731 --> 00:26:07,565
Will I have
a white dress
when I graduate?

489
00:26:07,650 --> 00:26:10,360
We'll see.
Neeley will probably have
to have shoes by that time.

490
00:26:10,486 --> 00:26:12,445
But, Mama.
Well, talk to him
about it.

491
00:26:12,529 --> 00:26:15,073
If you can get him
to quit coming through
the soles of his shoes.

492
00:26:15,157 --> 00:26:18,243
It's just because he's a boy.
All right, Mama.

493
00:26:18,327 --> 00:26:21,871
I will gladly do without
so my little brother
can be happy with new shoes.

494
00:26:21,956 --> 00:26:23,581
Little brother, my eye!

495
00:26:23,666 --> 00:26:26,292
That'll do! Francie,
you read too much.

496
00:26:26,377 --> 00:26:27,961
Well, hey, everybody.

497
00:26:28,045 --> 00:26:29,587
Hi, Aunt Sissy!
What did you bring us?

498
00:26:29,672 --> 00:26:31,673
I brung myself,
chickabiddies.
Ain't that enough?

499
00:26:31,757 --> 00:26:33,549
And a couple of magazines
from the dentist's.

500
00:26:33,634 --> 00:26:35,760
What does he need
'em for or me, either.

501
00:26:35,844 --> 00:26:38,263
I can't read
like my educated
little niece here.

502
00:26:38,347 --> 00:26:39,597
Hello, Katie,
my darling.

503
00:26:41,684 --> 00:26:43,268
Good evening, Sissy.

504
00:26:48,357 --> 00:26:51,192
Well, you look
fine, Katie.

505
00:26:51,735 --> 00:26:54,153
Yeah, I look fine.

506
00:26:54,863 --> 00:26:56,322
Who spilled the beans?

507
00:26:56,407 --> 00:26:58,700
I forgot.
It was old Barker's
day here.

508
00:26:58,784 --> 00:27:01,494
Where's Johnny?
I was kinda counting on him
to be in my corner.

509
00:27:01,578 --> 00:27:02,954
Sure. You and Johnny.

510
00:27:03,038 --> 00:27:04,247
Look, Katie,
I didn't tell you

511
00:27:04,331 --> 00:27:05,707
because I wanted to
bring Bill around.

512
00:27:05,791 --> 00:27:08,876
But I couldn't.
He's home sleeping.
He's a milkman, see?

513
00:27:09,795 --> 00:27:13,548
Listen. You're gonna
wish me happiness,
ain't you?

514
00:27:14,341 --> 00:27:17,593
Naturally, I'm going
to wish you happiness
this time, too.

515
00:27:18,053 --> 00:27:20,346
Golly, why can't
you skip to the part
where you forgive me?

516
00:27:20,431 --> 00:27:21,889
You're going to
before you're through.

517
00:27:21,974 --> 00:27:23,391
You know
I'll get around to
you in the end.

518
00:27:23,475 --> 00:27:25,727
Why can't you
just be human now
and get it over with?

519
00:27:26,270 --> 00:27:29,856
There ain't no one
like you to get around
a person in the whole world,

520
00:27:29,940 --> 00:27:31,149
unless it's Johnny.

521
00:27:31,233 --> 00:27:33,401
You're in time for pie.
Go on now and sit down!

522
00:27:33,485 --> 00:27:36,237
That's more like it.
That's my kid sister talking.

523
00:27:36,322 --> 00:27:39,657
Just coffee for me.
I gotta get home soon
and fix breakfast for Bill.

524
00:27:39,742 --> 00:27:42,160
Breakfast? At night?
Yeah. Ain't it a riot?

525
00:27:42,244 --> 00:27:45,079
We sleep all day long
with the shades pulled down
to keep out the sun

526
00:27:45,164 --> 00:27:47,165
and the windows shut
to keep out the noise.

527
00:27:47,249 --> 00:27:49,042
It's fun.
You don't live
like nobody else.

528
00:27:49,126 --> 00:27:50,376
No, you sure don't.

529
00:27:50,461 --> 00:27:53,629
Easy on the whip, kid.
Wait till you meet my Bill.
You and him will...

530
00:27:53,714 --> 00:27:56,716
Wouldn't you marry nobody
if they wasn't named Bill,
Aunt Sis?

531
00:27:56,800 --> 00:27:59,260
She might not
remember them
if they wasn't.

532
00:27:59,720 --> 00:28:03,056
Bill's got some other name.
Steve, I think it is.

533
00:28:03,140 --> 00:28:04,349
But I always liked Bill.

534
00:28:04,433 --> 00:28:06,809
A good man's name
with no stuck-up
about it.

535
00:28:07,478 --> 00:28:09,520
You'll be crazy
about him, Katie.
Yeah?

536
00:28:09,605 --> 00:28:12,065
But the question is
how will him
and you get along?

537
00:28:12,149 --> 00:28:14,984
It's wrong, Sissy.
I mean, the others...

538
00:28:15,069 --> 00:28:16,152
The others was wrong.

539
00:28:16,236 --> 00:28:17,862
What's right about
keeping on with a guy

540
00:28:17,946 --> 00:28:19,197
when you don't love
each other anymore?

541
00:28:19,281 --> 00:28:20,573
But it ain't
as easy as that.

542
00:28:20,657 --> 00:28:23,618
I think Aunt Sissy's right
about when love is dead.

543
00:28:25,079 --> 00:28:26,454
Now, look
what you started.

544
00:28:26,538 --> 00:28:28,581
It ain't nothing
to talk about
in front of them.

545
00:28:28,665 --> 00:28:30,792
Every time you come here,
you fill their heads with...

546
00:28:34,880 --> 00:28:36,798
Go on downstairs
for a while, kids.

547
00:28:36,882 --> 00:28:38,257
Your mama's got
a spanking up
her sleeve

548
00:28:38,342 --> 00:28:39,926
and she ain't
gonna feel right
until somebody gets it.

549
00:28:40,010 --> 00:28:41,594
Might as well
get it over with.

550
00:28:43,806 --> 00:28:46,432
You don't wanna frown
like that, snuggle pup.

551
00:28:47,226 --> 00:28:49,143
The fellas don't go
for that at all.

552
00:28:57,611 --> 00:28:59,487
All right, kid.
Let's have it,
the works.

553
00:28:59,571 --> 00:29:01,614
I'm a disgrace.
You don't know what
you're gonna do with me.

554
00:29:01,698 --> 00:29:02,824
You can hardly
face the neighbors

555
00:29:02,908 --> 00:29:03,991
with what they
must be saying.

556
00:29:04,076 --> 00:29:05,410
I'm old enough
to know better.

557
00:29:05,494 --> 00:29:06,744
Go on. Get it all
off your chest,

558
00:29:06,829 --> 00:29:07,995
then we can make up
and forget about it.

559
00:29:08,080 --> 00:29:11,082
That's right.
Talk your way out of it.
You probably will, too.

560
00:29:11,166 --> 00:29:12,291
What'd Mama have to say?

561
00:29:12,376 --> 00:29:13,668
You know Mama.
She don't say much.

562
00:29:13,752 --> 00:29:15,420
Sure. I know Mama.

563
00:29:15,504 --> 00:29:17,463
"Sissy is bad only where
the men are concerned,

564
00:29:17,548 --> 00:29:19,090
"but she's good
in her heart."

565
00:29:19,174 --> 00:29:21,926
But that ain't it, Sissy.
People got a right to talk.

566
00:29:22,010 --> 00:29:24,262
And the kids
are bound to hear,
and it ain't right for them.

567
00:29:24,346 --> 00:29:26,889
And you can get in trouble.
You ain't real sure
what happened,

568
00:29:26,974 --> 00:29:28,266
and there's laws about...

569
00:29:28,350 --> 00:29:29,809
Katie, so help me,
this time it's for keeps.

570
00:29:30,352 --> 00:29:32,228
I ain't even gonna
look at another guy.

571
00:29:32,312 --> 00:29:34,439
And as for the last one,
he can't be alive

572
00:29:34,523 --> 00:29:36,232
or I would have
heard from him.

573
00:29:36,316 --> 00:29:37,900
I've been pretty good.

574
00:29:37,985 --> 00:29:40,862
Seven years is a long time
to wait around
not being married.

575
00:29:41,363 --> 00:29:44,866
They said all you had to wait
was seven years and I waited.

576
00:29:45,284 --> 00:29:46,409
For the life of me,

577
00:29:46,493 --> 00:29:47,952
I don't know
what you're trying to
talk yourself into,

578
00:29:48,036 --> 00:29:49,454
but I got a feeling
it ain't right.

579
00:29:49,538 --> 00:29:50,872
All I know is
it can't be wrong,

580
00:29:50,956 --> 00:29:52,373
or I wouldn't feel
like I do about it.

581
00:29:52,833 --> 00:29:55,168
I'm dumb, sure,
but I know this much,

582
00:29:55,586 --> 00:29:58,171
if I feel bad
about something,
it's wrong.

583
00:29:58,630 --> 00:30:00,756
If I feel good,
it's right.

584
00:30:02,092 --> 00:30:05,720
You wouldn't get it, Katie.
You got all the breaks
I never had.

585
00:30:06,138 --> 00:30:08,306
You got the kids
and you got a guy

586
00:30:08,390 --> 00:30:10,558
you're clear
overboard about.
You're lucky.

587
00:30:11,018 --> 00:30:13,227
Yeah, and where does
crazy over somebody get you?

588
00:30:14,062 --> 00:30:15,855
It don't put
no pennies in the bank.

589
00:30:16,273 --> 00:30:18,566
It don't buy
no clothes for the kids
to go to school in.

590
00:30:19,902 --> 00:30:22,403
Maybe you got it better
not sticking to one guy.

591
00:30:24,072 --> 00:30:26,741
I wish, sometimes,
I wasn't so crazy over him.

592
00:30:26,825 --> 00:30:27,909
Hey, Katie.

593
00:30:27,993 --> 00:30:30,161
I won't have the kids
taking after him, either.

594
00:30:30,245 --> 00:30:33,831
Him and those
dreamy ways of his
I used to think were so fine.

595
00:30:33,916 --> 00:30:36,083
Not if I gotta cut it
right out of their hearts!

596
00:30:36,710 --> 00:30:38,085
Katie,
what are you saying?

597
00:30:40,839 --> 00:30:42,256
I don't know.

598
00:30:43,008 --> 00:30:44,592
Yes, you do.
You're saying plenty.

599
00:30:46,345 --> 00:30:47,678
What's happened
between you and Johnny?

600
00:30:48,514 --> 00:30:49,889
I don't know
what I'm saying.

601
00:30:49,973 --> 00:30:51,766
I don't know
what's come over me.

602
00:30:51,892 --> 00:30:53,601
Look, hon,
it's time we found out.

603
00:30:53,727 --> 00:30:55,561
Sure we got something
to talk about now.
I don't wanna.

604
00:30:55,646 --> 00:30:58,105
Uh-uh.
You're the kid sister.
You listen now.

605
00:30:59,107 --> 00:31:01,400
You was awful
crazy about Johnny.

606
00:31:01,485 --> 00:31:03,152
Don't tell me.
I seen you.

607
00:31:03,237 --> 00:31:05,029
It was like every woman
wants to be with a guy.

608
00:31:05,113 --> 00:31:06,447
Yeah.
All right,

609
00:31:07,533 --> 00:31:09,450
maybe Johnny
didn't turn out
just like you figured.

610
00:31:09,868 --> 00:31:13,996
Sure, he drinks and all,
and you're the one who's had
to make most of the living,

611
00:31:14,081 --> 00:31:15,790
but everybody's
got something.

612
00:31:16,333 --> 00:31:17,625
And you wasn't
crazy about Johnny

613
00:31:17,709 --> 00:31:18,960
because he was
gonna be a banker.

614
00:31:19,419 --> 00:31:21,837
It was on
account of...

615
00:31:21,922 --> 00:31:23,839
Well, on account of
how he laughed

616
00:31:24,716 --> 00:31:27,718
and how you felt
walking down the street
holding on to him

617
00:31:27,803 --> 00:31:29,720
and having other
women look at you.

618
00:31:29,972 --> 00:31:32,557
And the way he could
talk about things

619
00:31:33,850 --> 00:31:36,435
and the way
he had of saying hello
to everybody

620
00:31:37,020 --> 00:31:38,938
like he was giving
away something.

621
00:31:39,815 --> 00:31:41,941
That's what
you was crazy about,
and that ain't changed.

622
00:31:43,318 --> 00:31:46,654
I don't know.
Them things couldn't
change in Johnny,

623
00:31:47,823 --> 00:31:49,365
not even if he tried.

624
00:31:50,492 --> 00:31:54,328
He's just
different, kinda.
He always was.

625
00:31:55,831 --> 00:31:57,206
But he ain't changed.

626
00:31:59,501 --> 00:32:02,962
If there's been
any changing, hon,
maybe it's you.

627
00:32:04,506 --> 00:32:07,508
You still got all
you was crazy over,
ain't you?

628
00:32:08,010 --> 00:32:09,051
Yeah.

629
00:32:09,136 --> 00:32:11,095
Then thank your lucky stars
for what you got,
Katie Nolan,

630
00:32:11,179 --> 00:32:12,763
and take the rest
along with it!

631
00:32:12,848 --> 00:32:17,184
And you got a lot,
you can take it from me.
Don't think you haven't.

632
00:32:19,855 --> 00:32:23,274
I might have known,
starting out to
take you apart,

633
00:32:23,358 --> 00:32:25,901
I'd wind up with you
making me over.

634
00:32:27,237 --> 00:32:28,321
Nice going.

635
00:32:29,239 --> 00:32:32,199
Don't stir yourself, pal.
Thank you.

636
00:32:32,284 --> 00:32:33,367
Better go inside,
Alfred.

637
00:32:33,535 --> 00:32:34,619
How'd you come out,
Aunt Sis?

638
00:32:34,703 --> 00:32:38,456
No decision. It was a draw.
Your mom's bark
is worse than her bite.

639
00:32:38,540 --> 00:32:42,627
Look, tell me something.
When Papa's home, I bet...

640
00:32:42,711 --> 00:32:45,004
I bet him and Mama
laugh aplenty, don't they?

641
00:32:45,088 --> 00:32:46,797
You know,
like they always did?

642
00:32:46,882 --> 00:32:49,967
Sure. Pop can make
anybody laugh
when he wants to,

643
00:32:50,052 --> 00:32:51,385
except when he's drunk.

644
00:32:51,470 --> 00:32:53,346
"Sick," Neeley,
Mama said to call it!

645
00:32:53,430 --> 00:32:54,639
Okay. "Sick," then.

646
00:32:54,723 --> 00:32:57,808
Look, hon. Tell you
what you can do for me.

647
00:32:57,893 --> 00:32:59,477
Do all the laughing you can.

648
00:32:59,561 --> 00:33:01,520
You know,
keeps everybody healthy.

649
00:33:01,605 --> 00:33:02,647
Okay.

650
00:33:02,731 --> 00:33:05,107
Laughter is the singing
of the angels.

651
00:33:05,192 --> 00:33:08,653
You're a funny kid,
head full of
all them things,

652
00:33:08,737 --> 00:33:10,029
kinda like your pop.

653
00:33:10,113 --> 00:33:11,864
She tells lies
like Pop, too.

654
00:33:11,948 --> 00:33:13,157
He does not tell lies!

655
00:33:13,241 --> 00:33:14,325
Well, I don't know
what you call 'em.

656
00:33:14,409 --> 00:33:15,451
Time out!

657
00:33:15,535 --> 00:33:18,245
I've had enough battling
to last me for today.
Where did you get the skates?

658
00:33:18,330 --> 00:33:21,040
They aren't ours.
Papa said he'd
get us some, though.

659
00:33:21,124 --> 00:33:23,501
He didn't mean it.
He just said that.

660
00:33:23,585 --> 00:33:25,378
He did, too, mean it,
Neeley Nolan, and...

661
00:33:25,462 --> 00:33:27,254
Easy now!

662
00:33:27,339 --> 00:33:29,507
Kinda like your pop,
don't you, hon?

663
00:33:29,591 --> 00:33:32,093
He does mean it,
doesn't he,
Aunt Sissy?

664
00:33:32,177 --> 00:33:35,012
Sure, he means it.
He means it,
every word.

665
00:33:36,098 --> 00:33:39,308
But, well, you know,
sometimes things happen.

666
00:33:39,976 --> 00:33:42,436
But it kinda
ain't his fault. He...

667
00:33:42,938 --> 00:33:44,021
I tell you what.

668
00:33:44,106 --> 00:33:47,400
Let's make out like Johnny
gave you them skates like
he said and they're yours.

669
00:33:47,484 --> 00:33:49,068
Ain't gonna hurt nobody.
Aunt Sissy!

670
00:33:49,152 --> 00:33:51,195
No sense
in them things standin' around
and nobody usin' them.

671
00:33:51,279 --> 00:33:52,279
Come on.

672
00:33:54,700 --> 00:33:57,660
Here we go. Easy now.

673
00:33:57,744 --> 00:33:58,911
Isn't that fun? Huh?

674
00:33:58,995 --> 00:34:00,287
Can I put them on next,
Aunt Sissy?

675
00:34:00,497 --> 00:34:02,373
Sure, you can.
Mama! Mama! Mama!

676
00:34:02,457 --> 00:34:03,958
Hey! You come back
here with my skates!

677
00:34:04,042 --> 00:34:05,543
She's not gonna hurt 'em.

678
00:34:05,627 --> 00:34:06,877
Bring back
my daughter's skates!

679
00:34:06,962 --> 00:34:08,421
You was the one
that put them kids
up to it!

680
00:34:08,505 --> 00:34:10,715
Easy now! Nobody's hurt.
We only borrowed them.

681
00:34:10,799 --> 00:34:12,133
She's not going
off with them, Effie!

682
00:34:12,217 --> 00:34:14,385
Don't you dare
take up with that
woman like that!

683
00:34:14,469 --> 00:34:16,721
You poor little guy.
Do you put up
with that all the time?

684
00:34:18,223 --> 00:34:19,598
Hey, Officer!
Come on over here!

685
00:34:19,683 --> 00:34:20,766
Now this woman here,
she tried to...

686
00:34:20,851 --> 00:34:22,017
Break it up.
Take it easy.

687
00:34:22,102 --> 00:34:23,686
I'm sure glad
you come along,
handsome.

688
00:34:23,770 --> 00:34:26,313
You look like you could
whip a bunch of women
into line.

689
00:34:26,398 --> 00:34:28,566
Well, that's fine,
but now I suppose
somebody tells me

690
00:34:28,650 --> 00:34:30,109
what all the
excitement's about.

691
00:34:30,193 --> 00:34:31,736
She tried to steal
my little girl's skates!

692
00:34:31,820 --> 00:34:33,112
She tried to nab her.

693
00:34:33,196 --> 00:34:35,239
We only borrowed them
for just a minute.
Honest.

694
00:34:35,323 --> 00:34:36,907
That's right.
There wasn't nobody
using them.

695
00:34:36,992 --> 00:34:40,161
And a little fun and frolic
on a Saturday
never hurt nobody.

696
00:34:40,245 --> 00:34:41,912
Bet you know
all about that,
don't ya?

697
00:34:41,997 --> 00:34:44,957
If you think
you're gonna get out of it
making eyes at the law...

698
00:34:48,462 --> 00:34:50,421
I don't know what
the world's coming to!

699
00:34:50,505 --> 00:34:51,630
Get back a little bit,
buddy, huh?

700
00:34:51,715 --> 00:34:52,798
This lady
is my sister.

701
00:34:52,883 --> 00:34:56,218
She didn't mean any harm,
I'm quite sure she didn't.

702
00:34:58,847 --> 00:35:01,307
Well, as far as I can see,
there's been no harm done.

703
