00:58:56,742 --> 00:58:58,659
No, sir.
Not by a jugful
it ain't wrong.

1167
00:58:58,744 --> 00:59:01,037
Look, the house is here,
we're here
and the school's here.

1168
00:59:01,121 --> 00:59:04,207
Now, we wasn't
all thrown together
for no reason.

1169
00:59:05,626 --> 00:59:07,710
But we gotta keep
it kind of a secret.

1170
00:59:07,794 --> 00:59:09,879
You know,
you can't tell nobody

1171
00:59:09,963 --> 00:59:12,089
and you gotta be
extra good
to make up for it.

1172
00:59:12,299 --> 00:59:13,674
I will.

1173
00:59:14,927 --> 00:59:17,511
Look. There goes
Auntie now, I think.

1174
00:59:19,681 --> 00:59:22,225
It looks like
you got an uncle, too.

1175
00:59:23,685 --> 00:59:27,313
Now, I'm gonna show you a way
to your new school through
a beautiful, little park

1176
00:59:27,397 --> 00:59:29,023
and I know
right where it is.

1177
00:59:29,107 --> 00:59:32,151
And you can see
the seasons change
when you go.

1178
00:59:33,320 --> 00:59:34,946
Bend down, Papa.

1179
00:59:37,491 --> 00:59:39,367
"My cup runneth over."

1180
00:59:46,166 --> 00:59:47,917
It's dishonest,
that's what it is.

1181
00:59:48,001 --> 00:59:49,919
You're setting the child
an awful bad example.

1182
00:59:50,003 --> 00:59:51,587
Papa says if it
doesn't hurt anybody,

1183
00:59:51,672 --> 00:59:53,005
it's not dishonest
in your heart.

1184
00:59:53,090 --> 00:59:54,924
You two
and your fancy words.

1185
00:59:55,008 --> 00:59:56,801
How do you spell
"transfer," Francie?

1186
00:59:56,885 --> 01:00:02,848
T-R-A-N-S-F-E-R.

1187
01:00:03,475 --> 01:00:06,018
I'd rather be shot
than do this arithmetic.

1188
01:00:06,103 --> 01:00:08,229
It'll come to you, Sonny.
And another thing,

1189
01:00:08,313 --> 01:00:11,107
we kept Francie out a year
so she and Neeley
could be in the same class,

1190
01:00:11,191 --> 01:00:12,275
and she could
look after him.

1191
01:00:12,359 --> 01:00:15,444
And here, just the year
when they're getting ready
to graduate, you go and...

1192
01:00:15,529 --> 01:00:16,612
I tell you,
it's against the law,

1193
01:00:16,697 --> 01:00:17,655
and you're making
her live a lie

1194
01:00:17,739 --> 01:00:19,115
and I won't
have you doin' it!

1195
01:00:21,243 --> 01:00:23,661
I'm gonna do this
for her, Katie.

1196
01:00:23,745 --> 01:00:26,372
Maybe it's my fault or not
that there ain't much
I can give her.

1197
01:00:27,040 --> 01:00:29,917
But this is one thing
she's gonna have.

1198
01:00:35,299 --> 01:00:37,425
It'll make
an awful long walk
for your mornings.

1199
01:00:37,509 --> 01:00:39,093
I don't mind
getting up early.

1200
01:00:39,177 --> 01:00:40,636
And it'll be
much harder
on your shoes

1201
01:00:40,721 --> 01:00:42,596
and you won't have dresses
like the other children.

1202
01:00:42,681 --> 01:00:45,141
I promise to
wash down my dress
every single night.

1203
01:00:45,225 --> 01:00:47,476
How do you spell
"appreciate," Francie?

1204
01:00:47,561 --> 01:00:49,437
A-P-P...
Wait a minute.

1205
01:00:51,231 --> 01:00:55,735
R-E-C-I-A-T-E.

1206
01:00:56,653 --> 01:00:59,989
If the principal
swallows that story,
and I don't think he will,

1207
01:01:00,073 --> 01:01:04,702
I'll see what I can do
about making over that
checked dress of mine for you.

1208
01:01:15,881 --> 01:01:17,757
Why not?
My school's overcrowded
as it is.

1209
01:01:20,469 --> 01:01:22,595
This is Frances Nolan, class.

1210
01:01:22,679 --> 01:01:25,348
I'm sure you'll all make
her welcome to our school.

1211
01:01:25,432 --> 01:01:28,017
Now, that will be
your desk, Frances.

1212
01:01:48,497 --> 01:01:51,624
Run along, Sonny.
I ain't gonna
spill a penny.

1213
01:02:07,099 --> 01:02:09,475
Well, I guess
you got everything.

1214
01:02:12,521 --> 01:02:15,689
Neeley, our new fire escape
leads clear up onto the roof!

1215
01:02:15,774 --> 01:02:18,776
Whoever lives on the top floor
has got dibs on the roof!

1216
01:02:18,860 --> 01:02:21,070
Johnny ain't doing so well,
eh, Mrs. Nolan?

1217
01:02:21,154 --> 01:02:23,197
Just moving
near the sun.

1218
01:02:23,281 --> 01:02:27,159
Soon as we heard
Mrs. Waters was vacating,
we made up our minds.

1219
01:02:27,244 --> 01:02:29,370
I've been waiting to
see you, Mrs. Nolan.

1220
01:02:29,454 --> 01:02:32,623
There's something
I got to ask you,
a favor.

1221
01:02:32,707 --> 01:02:34,375
I better show you.

1222
01:02:34,459 --> 01:02:36,460
Hey.
Look at this thing!

1223
01:02:36,545 --> 01:02:39,630
Oh, boy! Just think,
we can have a lot of fun
running up and down that!

1224
01:02:39,714 --> 01:02:41,757
We ain't gonna let
anybody but us up there.

1225
01:02:41,842 --> 01:02:43,050
It's in here.

1226
01:02:43,135 --> 01:02:44,343
Look how high it is!

1227
01:02:50,016 --> 01:02:52,935
The late Mr. Waters
gave it to me
for a wedding present.

1228
01:02:53,019 --> 01:02:54,728
It won't go
down the stairs

1229
01:02:54,813 --> 01:02:58,190
and they want $15 to move it,
lowering it out the window.

1230
01:02:58,275 --> 01:03:00,943
Do you mind
my leaving it,
Mrs. Nolan?

1231
01:03:01,027 --> 01:03:03,487
It don't take up
much room,

1232
01:03:03,572 --> 01:03:06,615
and someday
when I get the $15,
I'll send back for it.

1233
01:03:06,700 --> 01:03:09,034
Why, sure,
I don't mind,
Mrs. Waters.

1234
01:03:09,119 --> 01:03:10,411
Can you play it?

1235
01:03:10,495 --> 01:03:11,745
No.

1236
01:03:11,830 --> 01:03:13,956
The neither
one of us could.

1237
01:03:14,040 --> 01:03:17,835
If it ain't too much trouble,
you could dust it off
once in a while,

1238
01:03:17,919 --> 01:03:20,796
and keep
the kitchen door open a little
so it won't get cold or damp.

1239
01:03:20,881 --> 01:03:22,590
I sure will.
Thank you.

1240
01:03:22,674 --> 01:03:26,385
I hope it won't be long
before you can
send back for it.

1241
01:03:28,555 --> 01:03:29,930
Have you got
the curtains?

1242
01:03:30,015 --> 01:03:31,557
Yes. They're coming.

1243
01:03:36,396 --> 01:03:37,771
Is it...

1244
01:03:39,232 --> 01:03:40,733
Is that...

1245
01:03:42,110 --> 01:03:45,112
Yeah, we kept a baby in it
about 40 years ago.

1246
01:03:46,031 --> 01:03:49,492
Well,
I was just wondering,
if you don't need it,

1247
01:03:49,576 --> 01:03:51,202
it would make a nice
handy little wash basket

1248
01:03:51,286 --> 01:03:53,204
and I'd be glad
to give you
a quarter for it.

1249
01:03:53,288 --> 01:03:56,999
Why, sure.
My Edgar's kids
is even too old.

1250
01:04:05,759 --> 01:04:08,010
Excuse me for asking,
Mrs. Nolan,

1251
01:04:08,094 --> 01:04:11,639
but it won't really make
a very handy wash basket.

1252
01:04:14,100 --> 01:04:17,436
Please don't say nothing.
I ain't told nobody yet.

1253
01:04:18,104 --> 01:04:20,439
It ain't always easy
when you're poor,

1254
01:04:20,607 --> 01:04:22,942
but it'll be
a blessing to you.

1255
01:04:24,361 --> 01:04:26,487
Yeah, sure.
Sure, it will.

1256
01:04:27,030 --> 01:04:28,322
But there must be!

1257
01:04:28,406 --> 01:04:29,823
I tell you, there ain't!

1258
01:04:32,202 --> 01:04:34,078
Well, goodbye,
Mrs. Nolan. Goodbye.

1259
01:04:34,162 --> 01:04:36,705
Goodbye,
and thank you
very much.

1260
01:04:36,790 --> 01:04:40,834
Don't forget we're supposed
to give him a beer,
or the price of one.

1261
01:04:40,919 --> 01:04:42,044
Well, I'm done.

1262
01:04:42,128 --> 01:04:43,754
I can't thank you
enough, Charlie.

1263
01:04:44,631 --> 01:04:47,341
Always glad to do
my customers a favor,
of course.

1264
01:04:47,425 --> 01:04:49,510
Well, we are
real grateful.

1265
01:04:49,970 --> 01:04:53,055
It ain't as though
I was in the regular
moving business.

1266
01:04:53,139 --> 01:04:56,642
We'll be taking ice from you,
same as usual, once a week.

1267
01:04:56,726 --> 01:04:58,727
Well, goodbye.

1268
01:04:58,812 --> 01:05:00,813
Goodbye, Charlie,
and thanks.

1269
01:05:00,897 --> 01:05:03,232
He worked
awful hard, Mama.

1270
01:05:03,316 --> 01:05:05,067
We moved up
to this flat
to save money,

1271
01:05:05,151 --> 01:05:07,528
and we're not gonna start
by throwing dimes away.

1272
01:05:07,612 --> 01:05:11,365
No, sir, there ain't
a bathtub anywhere.
I looked all over.

1273
01:05:14,160 --> 01:05:15,494
There's the tub,
young man.

1274
01:05:15,579 --> 01:05:17,288
Every Wednesday
and Saturday,
same as always.

1275
01:05:18,665 --> 01:05:20,291
It's Mr. Barker.

1276
01:05:22,419 --> 01:05:27,798
Well, it seems like
the Nolans have
come up in the world.

1277
01:05:27,882 --> 01:05:30,759
Yes, we're so
very, very fond
of the sunshine.

1278
01:05:30,844 --> 01:05:32,094
In Dublin's fair city

1279
01:05:32,178 --> 01:05:33,345
Where the girls
are so pretty...

1280
01:05:33,430 --> 01:05:36,223
Run and catch him
before he goes
to the old place.

1281
01:05:36,308 --> 01:05:37,516
Mr. Nolan happened
to be working

1282
01:05:37,601 --> 01:05:40,311
when we found
we could make the move.

1283
01:05:40,395 --> 01:05:43,564
Smaller than
your old flat,
ain't it?

1284
01:05:43,648 --> 01:05:45,441
I'm sorry I can't ask
you to sit, Mr. Barker.

1285
01:05:45,525 --> 01:05:47,067
I ain't even got
the coffee on yet.

1286
01:05:47,152 --> 01:05:49,361
But I got my
insurance money handy.

1287
01:05:49,446 --> 01:05:54,825
I suppose you're too busy
to listen to a bit of news
about your sister.

1288
01:05:56,369 --> 01:05:57,620
She...

1289
01:05:58,705 --> 01:06:00,706
She's gonna
have a baby.

1290
01:06:04,878 --> 01:06:08,464
Please tell my sister
she shouldn't make herself
such a stranger here.

1291
01:06:08,548 --> 01:06:10,424
I shall be very happy
to render your message.

1292
01:06:10,508 --> 01:06:11,634
Your receipts,
Mrs. Nolan.

1293
01:06:11,718 --> 01:06:13,594
Be sure to, now,
Mr. Barker.

1294
01:06:17,265 --> 01:06:18,932
Good day to you,
Mr. Nolan.

1295
01:06:19,017 --> 01:06:22,811
Well, I'm not one
to spoil a family party.
I'll be on my way.

1296
01:06:26,733 --> 01:06:29,568
Surprise, Papa.
Welcome to your new home.

1297
01:06:30,278 --> 01:06:33,864
Yeah. It is kind of
a surprise, all right.

1298
01:06:35,283 --> 01:06:37,701
Did you move up here
because it was
cheaper or because I...

1299
01:06:37,786 --> 01:06:41,163
We have to save
where we can.
Somebody's got to.

1300
01:06:41,247 --> 01:06:43,624
I don't mind
the extra stairs.

1301
01:06:55,470 --> 01:06:56,887
We can still
see the tree.

1302
01:06:56,971 --> 01:06:59,515
Pop,
the top-floor tenants,
the roof is theirs,

1303
01:06:59,599 --> 01:07:01,225
and I ain't gonna
let anybody up there

1304
01:07:01,309 --> 01:07:03,686
except Henny Gaddis,
because...

1305
01:07:03,770 --> 01:07:05,646
Hey. Does Pop know?

1306
01:07:05,730 --> 01:07:07,272
Flossie Gaddis
died last night.

1307
01:07:09,192 --> 01:07:10,693
The poor baby.

1308
01:07:11,528 --> 01:07:13,946
It was nice that her mama
got her all them
pretty dresses.

1309
01:07:14,030 --> 01:07:16,615
Only now the poor thing
will have to lie
in Potter's Field.

1310
01:07:18,201 --> 01:07:20,411
But she did have
the dresses.

1311
01:07:22,956 --> 01:07:25,124
You better show
your papa the piano.

1312
01:07:25,625 --> 01:07:29,336
Yeah, you better
show me the piano,
prima donna.

1313
01:07:31,297 --> 01:07:33,465
The lady
that was here left it.

1314
01:07:41,850 --> 01:07:43,642
It's got a nice tone.

1315
01:07:45,812 --> 01:07:47,354
It's all right.

1316
01:07:51,818 --> 01:07:55,362
Hey! Now that we got it,
maybe you can
take some lessons!

1317
01:07:56,823 --> 01:07:57,906
Nah.

1318
01:08:04,664 --> 01:08:09,084
Maxwellton braes are bonnie

1319
01:08:09,627 --> 01:08:13,464
Where early fa's the dew

1320
01:08:14,466 --> 01:08:19,219
And 'twas there
that Annie Laurie

1321
01:08:19,804 --> 01:08:30,856
Gave me her promise true

1322
01:08:31,691 --> 01:08:38,322
Which ne'er forgot will be

1323
01:08:40,784 --> 01:08:42,576
And for

1324
01:08:42,660 --> 01:08:48,832
Bonnie Annie Laurie

1325
01:08:51,002 --> 01:08:56,006
I would lay

1326
01:08:57,008 --> 01:08:59,468
me doon

1327
01:09:02,388 --> 01:09:05,557
and dee

1328
01:09:06,768 --> 01:09:11,396
I ain't never heard
you sing that before.
It's pretty. It's...

1329
01:09:11,481 --> 01:09:15,150
Maxwellton braes are bonnie

1330
01:09:15,235 --> 01:09:17,986
Where early fa's the dew

1331
01:09:18,530 --> 01:09:23,033
And 'twas there
that Annie Laurie

1332
01:09:23,117 --> 01:09:34,336
Gave me her promise true

1333
01:09:35,630 --> 01:09:41,927
Which ne'er forgot will be

1334
01:09:43,596 --> 01:09:47,766
And for Bonnie Annie

1335
01:09:49,561 --> 01:09:51,603
Laurie

1336
01:09:54,440 --> 01:09:57,276
I would lay

1337
01:09:58,528 --> 01:10:01,196
me doon

1338
01:10:03,908 --> 01:10:06,493
and dee

1339
01:10:11,791 --> 01:10:15,043
Well, this is
the beginning of a vacation
we've all looked forward to,

1340
01:10:15,128 --> 01:10:17,504
and I'm sure
we'll all enjoy
our holidays more

1341
01:10:17,589 --> 01:10:19,756
knowing we've helped
some unfortunate family

1342
01:10:19,841 --> 01:10:22,759
who'd have had no
Christmas dinner
without this basket.

1343
01:10:22,844 --> 01:10:25,762
And so a merry...
Oh, one last thing.

1344
01:10:25,847 --> 01:10:28,599
This extra pie
Miss Shilling brought in,

1345
01:10:28,683 --> 01:10:32,352
it's little
and a bit crushed,
but anybody want it?

1346
01:10:34,147 --> 01:10:36,523
My! What well-fed
boys and girls.

1347
01:10:37,734 --> 01:10:38,775
All right, class.

1348
01:10:38,860 --> 01:10:39,902
Miss McDonough!

1349
01:10:39,986 --> 01:10:40,944
Yes, Frances?

1350
01:10:41,029 --> 01:10:44,823
I just remembered.
I know a very
unfortunate family.

1351
01:10:44,908 --> 01:10:48,327
They live in a hovel.
They have two children,

1352
01:10:48,411 --> 01:10:51,788
little golden-haired twins,
and they're all starving.

1353
01:10:51,873 --> 01:10:54,082
The pie will probably
save their lives.

1354
01:10:54,459 --> 01:10:57,210
Then you should
take the pie,
by all means.

1355
01:10:57,879 --> 01:11:00,088
You can come and get it
when class is dismissed,

1356
01:11:00,173 --> 01:11:03,133
which is now.
A merry Christmas
to you all!

1357
01:11:08,181 --> 01:11:10,182
Here. Merry Christmas!

1358
01:11:12,977 --> 01:11:16,438
That was a very fine
Christmas spirit,
Frances,

1359
01:11:16,522 --> 01:11:19,650
but it seems
such a tiny pie to
save so many lives.

1360
01:11:19,734 --> 01:11:22,152
It won't seem small
to them, Miss McDonough.

1361
01:11:22,236 --> 01:11:23,695
Even a little pie
can look awful big

1362
01:11:23,780 --> 01:11:25,155
if you hadn't had
very much to eat

1363
01:11:25,239 --> 01:11:28,283
for days and days.
I'll have to tell them
to eat it slowly

1364
01:11:28,368 --> 01:11:32,120
because if they
eat it too fast on an
empty stomach, they'll...

1365
01:11:32,664 --> 01:11:33,747
They'll...

1366
01:11:35,917 --> 01:11:39,378
It isn't true.
It's all a lie!
I wanted it for myself!

1367
01:11:41,089 --> 01:11:44,466
I'll stay after school.
I'll do anything,
but don't send a note home!

1368
01:11:44,550 --> 01:11:47,552
I'm not going to
punish you, child,
for being hungry,

1369
01:11:47,637 --> 01:11:49,513
or having
an imagination.

1370
01:11:50,223 --> 01:11:52,891
You know, that's something
very few people have.

1371
01:11:52,976 --> 01:11:54,726
It's very precious.

1372
01:11:55,353 --> 01:11:59,064
But it can also
be dangerous unless
we learn how to use it.

1373
01:11:59,565 --> 01:12:03,986
Our everyday lives
are real and true,
aren't they?

1374
01:12:04,654 --> 01:12:08,156
But all the stories
in the world,
all the music

1375
01:12:08,241 --> 01:12:10,534
came out of
someone's imagination.

1376
01:12:10,618 --> 01:12:14,830
So, if we tell the truth
and write the lies,

1377
01:12:14,914 --> 01:12:16,164
then they aren't
lies anymore.

1378
01:12:16,249 --> 01:12:18,166
They become stories,

1379
01:12:18,251 --> 01:12:21,503
like some of
the very nice compositions
you've written, Frances.

1380
01:12:21,587 --> 01:12:23,171
Like the one about
my father taking me

1381
01:12:23,256 --> 01:12:25,465
to see the cotton fields
down south.

1382
01:12:25,550 --> 01:12:26,967
We didn't really go.

1383
01:12:27,468 --> 01:12:29,177
I rather imagined
you didn't.

1384
01:12:30,096 --> 01:12:32,639
But don't you think
it would be still better

1385
01:12:32,724 --> 01:12:36,560
if you'd write
about the things
you really know about

1386
01:12:36,644 --> 01:12:38,603
and then add to them
with your imagination?

1387
01:12:39,647 --> 01:12:44,568
Even stories
shouldn't be just,
well, pipe dreams.

1388
01:12:45,236 --> 01:12:47,696
Pipe-dreamers can be
very lovable people

1389
01:12:47,780 --> 01:12:50,949
but they
don't help anybody,
not even themselves.

1390
01:12:51,451 --> 01:12:55,704
Now, think about it a little,
and have a merry Christmas.

1391
01:12:58,708 --> 01:13:00,459
And enjoy your pie.

1392
01:13:01,044 --> 01:13:04,421
Yes, Miss McDonough.
Thank you, Miss McDonough.

1393
01:13:12,680 --> 01:13:14,222
For God's sakes!
Where you been?

1394
01:13:14,307 --> 01:13:15,974
You were supposed
to meet me...

1395
01:13:16,184 --> 01:13:17,225
Where'd you swipe that?

1396
01:13:17,310 --> 01:13:19,394
Neeley, I'm going
to be a writer.

1397
01:13:19,479 --> 01:13:21,855
All right,
but let's eat the pie.

1398
01:13:22,982 --> 01:13:25,108
Come on,
we gotta see about
our Christmas tree!

1399
01:13:25,193 --> 01:13:27,819
Golly!
It's still there,
isn't it?

1400
01:13:33,409 --> 01:13:35,202
Yeah,
it's still here.

1401
01:13:35,286 --> 01:13:37,162
He ain't got much time
left to sell it.

1402
01:13:37,246 --> 01:13:39,831
Go on. Beat it!
You know I ain't gonna
throw them till midnight.

1403
01:13:39,916 --> 01:13:42,709
What are you trying to do,
block the sidewalk,
keep customers out?

1404
01:13:42,794 --> 01:13:46,088
Hey! You don't own
the sidewalk!
Free country, ain't it?

1405
01:13:46,172 --> 01:13:48,215
How about this one,
madam?

1406
01:13:49,675 --> 01:13:52,969
No, that one's too big.
I want a small one.

1407
01:13:53,054 --> 01:13:55,472
I got just what you want.
Come over here, lady.

1408
01:13:55,556 --> 01:13:58,683
Well, now,
that's more like it!
That's the size.

1409
01:13:59,018 --> 01:14:01,311
It's awful big to
get throwed at you.

1410
01:14:01,395 --> 01:14:03,814
Why does he have to
throw them at us,
anyway?

1411
01:14:03,898 --> 01:14:06,858
Why can't he
just give them to us
if he don't sell them?

1412
01:14:06,943 --> 01:14:08,860
If he just gave them away,
everybody would wait.

1413
01:14:08,945 --> 01:14:11,196
He'd never sell
any of 'em.

1414
01:14:14,033 --> 01:14:15,450
Smells good.

1415
01:14:20,123 --> 01:14:21,706
There she goes!

1416
01:14:22,625 --> 01:14:24,084
Hey, I stumbled!

1417
01:14:24,168 --> 01:14:25,460
Go on! Beat it!
Who's next?

1418
01:14:25,586 --> 01:14:26,878
Come on,
give me a chance.
I'm next.

1419
01:14:26,963 --> 01:14:29,131
All right,
here she goes.

1420
01:14:30,675 --> 01:14:31,675
Got it, didn't I?

1421
01:14:31,759 --> 01:14:33,260
All right, take it!
Go home!

1422
01:14:34,262 --> 01:14:35,804
Now, who wants
to try this one?

1423
01:14:35,888 --> 01:14:38,014
Who's man enough
for this big one
right here?

1424
01:14:38,099 --> 01:14:39,975
I can take anything
you got, mister. Let her...

1425
01:14:40,059 --> 01:14:41,726
I'm next!
That's my tree!

1426
01:14:42,061 --> 01:14:43,478
You're too small.
Go home.

1427
01:14:43,563 --> 01:14:46,106
Me and my brother,
we ain't too small
together.

1428
01:14:46,190 --> 01:14:47,190
Spunky, huh?

1429
01:14:47,275 --> 01:14:49,276
All right,
but if one of you drop,

1430
01:14:49,402 --> 01:14:51,444
you're not gonna
get the tree.

1431
01:14:52,947 --> 01:14:54,739
There she goes!

1432
01:14:56,576 --> 01:14:58,493
That a girl!
You got it!

1433
01:14:58,578 --> 01:15:01,955
Okay, you got it coming.
Go ahead! Who's next?

1434
01:15:04,625 --> 01:15:07,502
Quit worrying
about them, Katie.
They'll be home pretty quick.

1435
01:15:07,587 --> 01:15:09,796
They ain't old enough
to be out this late.

1436
01:15:09,881 --> 01:15:12,632
Johnny should have made them
tell what they was up to.

1437
01:15:12,717 --> 01:15:14,968
No telling
what's likely to happen
if Francie gets a notion...

1438
01:15:15,052 --> 01:15:16,845
They'll be all right.

1439
01:15:29,901 --> 01:15:32,110
Well, I guess
we better get on home.

1440
01:15:32,612 --> 01:15:33,695
I'll see them tomorrow.

1441
01:15:33,779 --> 01:15:35,030
No, don't go!

1442
01:15:39,076 --> 01:15:41,036
Hey, Pa! Hey, Ma!

1443
01:15:41,120 --> 01:15:42,537
Hey, Ma!

1444
01:15:45,124 --> 01:15:46,249
Look!

1445
01:15:47,251 --> 01:15:50,629
Holy smoke!
Will you look what
they've went and done?

1446
01:15:52,715 --> 01:15:55,926
They're trying to
make a Christmas.
Help 'em, kid.

1447
01:16:01,224 --> 01:16:02,724
We got it throwed at us!
Well, sure,

1448
01:16:02,808 --> 01:16:05,894
I was only wondering
if you couldn't use
a little help.

1449
01:16:05,978 --> 01:16:07,395
Come on, come on,
come on.

1450
01:16:07,521 --> 01:16:08,897
How in Jerusalem
did you...

1451
01:16:08,981 --> 01:16:11,191
Look, Papa!
Look at my face, Pop!
Look at my face!

1452
01:16:11,275 --> 01:16:12,692
Nobody around here
ever saw a tree
like that!

1453
01:16:12,777 --> 01:16:14,236
Look at my face
if you don't believe it.

1454
01:16:14,320 --> 01:16:16,112
And I see you got the law
on your side, too.

1455
01:16:16,197 --> 01:16:18,657
Merry Christmas, Mr. Nolan!
And it looks like
you're gonna have one.

1456
01:16:18,741 --> 01:16:20,283
Same to you,
Mr. McShane,
and thanks.

1457
01:16:20,368 --> 01:16:21,910
Merry Christmas,
Mr. Nolan.

1458
01:16:21,994 --> 01:16:23,078
Merry Christmas,
Miss Maggie.

1459
01:16:23,162 --> 01:16:24,537
Isn't this a wonderful
Christmas, Papa?

1460
01:16:24,622 --> 01:16:25,914
It is now,
prima donna.

1461
01:16:25,998 --> 01:16:27,624
Imagine us having
a tree like that,

1462
01:16:28,542 --> 01:16:30,627
and the nicest kids
in the world, I guess.

1463
01:16:33,881 --> 01:16:36,424
Merry Christmas,
everybody!
Merry Christmas!

1464
01:16:36,509 --> 01:16:38,051
God bless you,
Mr. Nolan.

1465
01:16:38,803 --> 01:16:40,220
Merry Christmas, Neeley!

1466
01:16:40,346 --> 01:16:41,805
Merry Christmas!

1467
01:16:45,726 --> 01:16:47,227
He ain't any older
than they are.

1468
01:16:47,478 --> 01:16:52,607
Round yon
virgin mother and child

1469
01:16:52,900 --> 01:16:57,946
Holy infant
so tender and mild

1470
01:16:58,030 --> 01:16:59,030
Merry Christmas.

1471
01:16:59,115 --> 01:17:07,205
Sleep in heavenly peace

1472
01:17:07,290 --> 01:17:10,625
Silent night, holy...

1473
01:17:14,797 --> 01:17:15,922
Here!

1474
01:17:20,469 --> 01:17:22,178
Put it up
higher, Bill!

1475
01:17:22,263 --> 01:17:23,346
Steve's the name.

1476
01:17:23,431 --> 01:17:24,723
That's better, Bill.

1477
01:17:25,224 --> 01:17:26,975
Old itchy underwear!

1478
01:17:28,144 --> 01:17:31,062
But look at all the fun
you can have scratching!

1479
01:17:32,398 --> 01:17:33,523
Thank you, Mama.

1480
01:17:33,607 --> 01:17:35,317
You know
you hate them.

1481
01:17:35,401 --> 01:17:37,110
They're fine, Mama.

1482
01:17:43,075 --> 01:17:45,285
I got something
for you, too, Mama.

1483
01:17:45,369 --> 01:17:49,331
Johnny. It was real nice
of your friend Mr. McGarrity

1484
01:17:49,415 --> 01:17:52,167
to send over
those candy canes
to the kids.

1485
01:17:52,251 --> 01:17:53,335
Yeah.

1486
01:17:53,753 --> 01:17:56,379
Here. I made this
candle for today.

1487
01:17:56,464 --> 01:17:59,007
You better light it now.
It's time.

1488
01:18:01,052 --> 01:18:03,178
Merry Christmas, Mama,
from me and Neeley.

1489
01:18:06,182 --> 01:18:08,016
Oh, it's pretty.

1490
01:18:08,684 --> 01:18:09,809
What is it?

1491
01:18:09,894 --> 01:18:11,102
Rose water
and glycerin.

1492
01:18:11,270 --> 01:18:13,271
You rub it
on your hands.

1493
01:18:14,523 --> 01:18:17,317
This is for you, Papa,
from me and Neeley.

1494
01:18:20,237 --> 01:18:21,446
My!

1495
01:18:23,991 --> 01:18:25,867
I'll be quite the thing,
won't I?

1496
01:18:25,951 --> 01:18:28,203
I think it's silly,
but Francie said

1497
01:18:28,287 --> 01:18:31,206
Papa was always talking about
what nice hands you got.

1498
01:18:31,290 --> 01:18:35,043
It cost a dime,
but we had a seltzer bottle
top in the junk.

1499
01:18:39,131 --> 01:18:42,217
It's a watch fob.
It's made out
of shoelaces.

1500
01:18:42,301 --> 01:18:44,636
I wove it on a spool
with nails.

1501
01:18:45,638 --> 01:18:50,058
Well, if that ain't
about the nicest thing
I ever did see.

1502
01:18:50,142 --> 01:18:52,727
Maybe it's kinda silly,
you not having a watch.

1503
01:18:52,812 --> 01:18:55,688
Well, now, madam,
we're all out of
mushrooms under glass,

1504
01:18:55,773 --> 01:18:58,024
but I can
tell you the time.

1505
01:18:58,651 --> 01:19:01,486
That's the nicest present
I ever did get, prima donna.

1506
01:19:01,570 --> 01:19:03,571
And thank you, too, Son.

1507
01:19:03,656 --> 01:19:06,866
You're welcome. I guess
the shoelaces was mine.

1508
01:19:08,077 --> 01:19:09,077
It was silly.

1509
01:19:09,161 --> 01:19:10,495
There ain't nothing
silly on Christmas.

1510
01:19:10,579 --> 01:19:13,832
I got a little
present here.

1511
01:19:17,294 --> 01:19:19,003
Like I was saying,
I got...

1512
01:19:19,088 --> 01:19:20,255
Merry Christmas,
Miss Francie.

1513
01:19:20,339 --> 01:19:23,174
Come on. They're in here.
It's Mr. McShane.

1514
01:19:23,259 --> 01:19:24,342
I hope I'm not intruding.

1515
01:19:24,427 --> 01:19:25,718
Merry Christmas,
Mr. McShane.

1516
01:19:25,803 --> 01:19:26,928
Merry Christmas!

1517
01:19:27,012 --> 01:19:28,471
Merry Christmas.
I was just...

1518
01:19:28,556 --> 01:19:29,681
Hello, handsome.

1519
01:19:29,765 --> 01:19:31,391
Mrs. Edwards.

1520
01:19:31,475 --> 01:19:35,061
I was just passing,
and I happened to see
the light still burning

1521
01:19:35,146 --> 01:19:36,354
and I got to thinking

1522
01:19:36,439 --> 01:19:39,441
that I'd like to have
a hand in decorating
that fine Christmas tree.

1523
01:19:39,525 --> 01:19:40,775
I see somebody's
already provided.

1524
01:19:40,860 --> 01:19:43,111
We can always
use more of them,
Mr. McShane.

1525
01:19:43,195 --> 01:19:45,029
Thank you kindly.

1526
01:19:45,489 --> 01:19:47,949
Won't you come in
and have a cup
of coffee with us?

1527
01:19:48,033 --> 01:19:51,828
Thanks, no.
This evening's
for families.

1528
01:19:51,912 --> 01:19:53,455
And I got to be
getting home now,

1529
01:19:53,539 --> 01:19:56,958
so I'll say goodbye
and merry Christmas
to everybody.

1530
01:19:57,042 --> 01:19:59,544
Thank you, Mr. McShane.
Merry Christmas!

1531
01:19:59,712 --> 01:20:01,421
That was mighty
nice of him.

1532
01:20:01,547 --> 01:20:03,256
Mr. McShane's
a fine man.

1533
01:20:03,340 --> 01:20:06,134
He's, I think,
sometimes a lonely man.

1534
01:20:06,218 --> 01:20:09,637
Like I was saying,
I got something here.

1535
01:20:09,722 --> 01:20:13,725
I mean,
I got a present for somebody
that ain't exactly here.

1536
01:20:13,809 --> 01:20:17,312
Grandma helped me pick it out.
It's for you know who.

1537
01:20:19,023 --> 01:20:22,108
Bill, it's beautiful.
Look, everybody!

1538
01:20:24,445 --> 01:20:26,571
Bill, darling,
I've never been
so happy!

1539
01:20:27,239 --> 01:20:29,032
I'm gonna get some coffee.

1540
01:20:42,421 --> 01:20:43,588
Katie?

1541
01:20:48,427 --> 01:20:49,552
Yeah.

1542
01:20:49,845 --> 01:20:50,970
I'm glad for ya.

1543
01:20:53,849 --> 01:20:56,309
I don't know.
I'm scared, I guess.

1544
01:20:56,393 --> 01:20:59,521
You got no call to be.
Look how swell
them two are.

1545
01:20:59,605 --> 01:21:01,105
Yeah, they are.

1546
01:21:02,650 --> 01:21:04,442
You told Johnny yet?

1547
01:21:06,445 --> 01:21:09,322
Well, maybe you ought to.
It might help him.

1548
01:21:09,949 --> 01:21:11,074
Yeah.

1549
01:21:15,579 --> 01:21:17,789
We better take
the coffee in.

1550
01:21:18,374 --> 01:21:21,793
You're a fine girl, Katie.
I never said any different.

1551
01:21:42,856 --> 01:21:46,568
That's for nothing, Johnny,
except maybe being a nice guy.

1552
01:21:48,487 --> 01:21:50,405
Coffee, everybody!

1553
01:22:04,253 --> 01:22:06,546
Well, I guess
that's about all.

1554
01:22:06,964 --> 01:22:09,507
Johnny, I got to
tell ya something.

1555
01:22:09,883 --> 01:22:12,969
Maybe it ain't
the right time,
and maybe it is.

1556
01:22:13,637 --> 01:22:15,763
The reason
I moved us up here...

1557
01:22:16,932 --> 01:22:18,182
We're gonna have
a baby, Johnny.

1558
01:22:18,267 --> 01:22:20,602
That's why I've been
scrimpin' so much
and tryin' so hard to save.

1559
01:22:20,686 --> 01:22:21,936
That's...

1560
01:22:23,856 --> 01:22:27,483
Well, I'm awful glad,
Katie, if you are.

1561
01:22:27,568 --> 01:22:29,027
There's a lot we got
to think about, Johnny.

1562
01:22:29,111 --> 01:22:30,612
I know!
But we'll make out.

1563
01:22:30,696 --> 01:22:32,572
Maybe things
will be different.

1564
01:22:32,656 --> 01:22:34,657
And we'll have one
to grow up with
all over again.

1565
01:22:34,742 --> 01:22:36,743
I got things
all figured out.

1566
01:22:36,827 --> 01:22:40,330
I ought to be able
to work until,
well, anyway, April,

1567
01:22:40,414 --> 01:22:43,041
and then Francie
will have to leave school
and take out a working paper.

1568
01:22:43,125 --> 01:22:44,876
She's young,
but with what
she can make,

1569
01:22:44,960 --> 01:22:46,127
we ought to be
able to make out.

1570
01:22:46,211 --> 01:22:47,503
But we can't
do that, Katie!

1571
01:22:47,588 --> 01:22:49,339
I don't like it any better
than you do, Johnny.

1572
01:22:49,423 --> 01:22:51,924
But I thought and I thought,
and there ain't no other way.

1573
01:22:52,009 --> 01:22:54,969
And, Johnny, you got to
help with something.
She listens to you.

1574
01:22:55,054 --> 01:22:58,431
You got to quit
gettin' her so all excited
about her schoolin'.

1575
01:22:58,515 --> 01:23:00,058
But why can't it
be Neeley?

1576
01:23:00,142 --> 01:23:02,060
He's the boy,
and he don't care
like she does!

1577
01:23:02,144 --> 01:23:03,519
Well, maybe that's why.

1578
01:23:03,604 --> 01:23:05,813
Maybe it'll do her good
to get out in the world,

1579
01:23:05,898 --> 01:23:08,149
and learn how to
take care of herself,

1580
01:23:08,233 --> 01:23:09,525
learn somethin' practical
while she's young.

1581
01:23:09,610 --> 01:23:11,527
She's got to
learn someday.

1582
01:23:11,654 --> 01:23:13,571
Well, there must be
another way!

1583
01:23:15,157 --> 01:23:18,326
I don't know. I'll try
and swing anything.
I'll do anything.

1584
01:23:18,410 --> 01:23:20,078
We can't count
on that, Johnny.

1585
01:23:24,083 --> 01:23:27,543
Don't look at me
like that, Johnny.
It ain't my fault.

1586
01:23:30,714 --> 01:23:33,925
It ain't your fault either,
I guess. I don't know.

1587
01:23:35,219 --> 01:23:37,929
Anyway, one member of
the Nolan family'll

1588
01:23:38,013 --> 01:23:39,764
get to graduate,
and she come close.

1589
01:23:39,848 --> 01:23:41,474
That's somethin'.

1590
01:23:45,562 --> 01:23:48,981
You better put out the light,
and let's get some rest.

1591
01:24:14,049 --> 01:24:15,049
Oh!

1592
01:24:15,426 --> 01:24:17,927
I thought you'd be asleep,
prima donna.

1593
01:24:18,303 --> 01:24:20,930
Uh-uh.
I've been thinking.

1594
01:24:22,975 --> 01:24:26,728
I might be going
to be a writer.
I've just about decided.

1595
01:24:28,689 --> 01:24:31,023
I knew you
when you was gonna
be a lady fireman.

1596
01:24:32,192 --> 01:24:34,944
Don't joke, Papa.
I'm serious.

1597
01:24:35,529 --> 01:24:37,321
All right, baby.

1598
01:24:37,489 --> 01:24:42,243
All I meant
was maybe it's better
not to get your heart set

1599
01:24:42,327 --> 01:24:46,330
on just one thing,
in case something happens.

1600
01:24:46,415 --> 01:24:49,333
She said,
Miss McDonough,
I mean,

1601
01:24:50,252 --> 01:24:56,007
she said maybe I could be.
She said I have imagination.

1602
01:24:57,092 --> 01:24:58,718
Do you think
I have, Papa?

1603
01:24:58,802 --> 01:25:00,678
Sure you have, baby.

1604
01:25:00,763 --> 01:25:03,222
Them compositions of yours
are sure fine, but...

1605
01:25:03,307 --> 01:25:05,600
She said I'd have
to work hard.

1606
01:25:05,976 --> 01:25:08,686
She said imagination
wasn't any good

1607
01:25:08,854 --> 01:25:11,606
if you were just
a pipe-dreamer
about it.

1608
01:25:11,857 --> 01:25:16,110
You didn't help
anybody that way,
not even yourself, she said.

1609
01:25:16,528 --> 01:25:20,823
Yeah, I see.
A pipe-dreamer.

1610
01:25:22,409 --> 01:25:24,952
I'm not putting it
good like she did.

1611
01:25:25,370 --> 01:25:28,748
I wish you
could've heard her.
She was wonderful.

1612
01:25:30,083 --> 01:25:33,628
Forever and ever,
I'll be glad you helped me
go to that school, Papa.

1613
01:25:33,712 --> 01:25:35,588
You kind of
like that school,
don't you, baby?

1614
01:25:36,215 --> 01:25:39,217
Yes. Oh, yes.

1615
01:25:40,052 --> 01:25:44,222
And she said lots more.
I've been trying to remember.

1616
01:25:46,683 --> 01:25:49,268
She said even if
you have imagination,

1617
01:25:49,353 --> 01:25:51,479
it's better to write about
the things you know about

1618
01:25:51,563 --> 01:25:53,731
so they'll be true.

1619
01:25:54,983 --> 01:25:56,984
And the way things are.

1620
01:25:57,653 --> 01:25:58,653
Only...

1621
01:25:58,737 --> 01:26:00,071
Only what, baby?

1622
01:26:00,697 --> 01:26:03,825
Papa, the people in the hall
when we brought up the tree,

1623
01:26:03,909 --> 01:26:06,536
the look on their faces,
all friendly and nice.

1624
01:26:06,620 --> 01:26:10,414
Why can't people
be like that all the time,
not just on Christmas?

1625
01:26:11,667 --> 01:26:15,419
Well, I guess
it's because...

1626
01:26:17,965 --> 01:26:19,924
Well, I don't know.

1627
01:26:21,385 --> 01:26:23,845
Maybe it's because
Christmas is like
people really are

1628
01:26:23,929 --> 01:26:25,847
and the other
part ain't true.

1629
01:26:26,098 --> 01:26:27,557
And with that
imagination of yours,

1630
01:26:27,641 --> 01:26:29,559
if you think
about it hard enough,

1631
01:26:29,643 --> 01:26:31,519
you know,
like it ought to be...

1632
01:26:31,603 --> 01:26:33,729
But when you
get to thinking,

1633
01:26:33,814 --> 01:26:35,356
Papa, the people
in the stories,

1634
01:26:35,440 --> 01:26:37,984
they don't just live
happily ever after,
do they?

1635
01:26:38,068 --> 01:26:39,193
No, baby, but...

1636
01:26:39,278 --> 01:26:41,070
But the trouble is,

1637
01:26:41,947 --> 01:26:44,740
it doesn't feel good
when you think about
things like that,

1638
01:26:45,909 --> 01:26:49,287
I mean,
like they really are.

1639
01:26:50,873 --> 01:26:53,875
You better stick
out your tongue,
prima donna.

1640
01:26:56,879 --> 01:26:58,880
It's just like I thought.

1641
01:26:59,798 --> 01:27:02,592
You got a bad case,
a very bad case.

1642
01:27:03,051 --> 01:27:04,427
Case of what, Papa?

1643
01:27:05,095 --> 01:27:07,013
A very bad case
of growing up.

1644
01:27:08,599 --> 01:27:10,224
That's all it is.

1645
01:27:12,603 --> 01:27:17,315
It ain't fun sometimes,
but don't you be afraid.

1646
01:27:18,233 --> 01:27:20,985
I don't want you
should ever be afraid.

1647
01:27:23,989 --> 01:27:25,823
You're so nice, Papa.

1648
01:27:26,408 --> 01:27:29,785
I guess it's better
if you don't just
stay young all your life.

1649
01:27:29,870 --> 01:27:32,705
It'll be much nicer
growing up.

1650
01:27:35,208 --> 01:27:36,542
Yeah.

1651
01:27:39,630 --> 01:27:43,049
Then you get to see things
like they really are.

1652
01:28:13,497 --> 01:28:14,747
Good night, baby.

1653
01:28:15,332 --> 01:28:16,624
Good night, Papa.

1654
01:28:18,460 --> 01:28:20,169
I'm sleepy now.

1655
01:28:21,797 --> 01:28:24,966
That's fine, baby,
just fine.

1656
01:28:51,868 --> 01:28:54,245
Ain't ya comin'
to bed, Johnny?

1657
01:28:54,329 --> 01:28:56,664
No. I'm gonna take
a little walk.

1658
01:28:56,748 --> 01:28:59,083
Don't start drinking,
not tonight, Johnny.

1659
01:28:59,501 --> 01:29:01,794
I won't, Katie.
I won't.

1660
01:29:27,320 --> 01:29:30,531
Well, did he
go out on a job,
do you know?

1661
01:29:30,615 --> 01:29:33,325
If he did,
he didn't get it
through us.

1662
01:29:35,120 --> 01:29:36,579
Thank you.

1663
01:29:45,922 --> 01:29:48,507
How are you, Mrs. Nolan?
And happy new year to you.

1664
01:29:48,592 --> 01:29:50,676
Same to you,
Mr. McGarrity.

1665
01:29:51,636 --> 01:29:54,930
I just came to...

1666
01:29:56,224 --> 01:29:58,559
Well, I happened
to be passing by,
and I thought I'd run in

1667
01:29:58,643 --> 01:30:00,895
and thank you for
the candy canes
you sent us.

1668
01:30:00,979 --> 01:30:02,271
It was nice of ya.

1669
01:30:02,355 --> 01:30:03,773
That's all right.
It wasn't much.

1670
01:30:04,357 --> 01:30:06,358
Well, it was
nice of you.

1671
01:30:09,988 --> 01:30:11,572
Good night, Mr. McGarrity.
Good night, Mrs. Nolan.

1672
01:30:11,656 --> 01:30:13,032
Mrs. Nolan.

1673
01:30:14,826 --> 01:30:18,662
Johnny ain't here.
He ain't been here
since before Christmas.

1674
01:30:38,975 --> 01:30:41,894
I'm afraid it's bad news
I'm bringing you, Mrs. Nolan.

1675
01:30:41,978 --> 01:30:43,979
Our station
just got a report
that Mr. Nolan

1676
01:30:44,064 --> 01:30:46,107
was found over in
Manhattan very sick.

1677
01:30:46,191 --> 01:30:48,442
He's been taken
to a hospital.

1678
01:30:49,361 --> 01:30:51,445
See that Neeley
gets to school on time
in the morning.

1679
01:30:51,530 --> 01:30:52,947
There's an apple
for your lunches.

1680
01:30:53,031 --> 01:30:55,950
The report said
that he just collapsed

1681
01:30:56,034 --> 01:30:57,952
right in the doorway
of an employment agency.

1682
01:30:58,036 --> 01:30:59,912
And he'd just been
going out on a job.

1683
01:30:59,996 --> 01:31:02,331
A sandhog
in a tunnel,
they said.

1684
01:31:02,415 --> 01:31:04,041
And he hadn't been
drinking, ma'am.

1685
01:31:04,126 --> 01:31:07,211
He'd been waiting there
a long time for the job.

1686
01:31:08,171 --> 01:31:09,797
He was just sick.

1687
01:31:16,304 --> 01:31:17,638
We did everything
we could.

1688
01:31:17,722 --> 01:31:19,265
Yeah, sure. I know.

1689
01:31:20,809 --> 01:31:22,768
What are you writing down
that he died from, Doctor?

1690
01:31:22,853 --> 01:31:26,438
Acute alcoholism
and pneumonia.
One led to the other.

1691
01:31:27,524 --> 01:31:30,943
I don't want you
to write down that
he died like that.

1692
01:31:31,570 --> 01:31:33,696
Put just the pneumonia.
I can't do that.

1693
01:31:33,780 --> 01:31:36,323
Pneumonia was
the direct cause of death,
but the alcoholism was...

1694
01:31:36,408 --> 01:31:37,700
Look, he's dead.

1695
01:31:37,784 --> 01:31:40,494
I got two nice kids
that are gonna grow up
to amount to somethin'.

1696
01:31:40,579 --> 01:31:44,790
Why do you have to make it
hard by sayin' their father
died from the drink

1697
01:31:45,500 --> 01:31:47,793
when that's only
a little piece
of the truth?

1698
01:31:47,878 --> 01:31:51,714
He wasn't drinkin'.
They said so.
He was out lookin' for work.

1699
01:31:53,884 --> 01:31:55,426
Why don't you
put that down?

1700
01:31:58,054 --> 01:32:02,099
Cause of death,
pneumonia.

1701
01:32:06,897 --> 01:32:08,856
"Everlasting rest
and happiness

1702
01:32:08,940 --> 01:32:12,067
"through the infinite merits
of Jesus Christ.

1703
01:32:12,152 --> 01:32:16,739
"Oh, God,
great and omnipotent judge
of the living and the dead,

1704
01:32:16,823 --> 01:32:19,533
"before whom
we are all to appear
after this short life

1705
01:32:20,076 --> 01:32:22,077
"to render an account
of our work.

1706
01:32:22,162 --> 01:32:24,038
"Let our hearts,
we pray Thee,

1707
01:32:24,122 --> 01:32:26,624
"be deeply moved at
the sight of this death.

1708
01:32:26,708 --> 01:32:30,169
"And while we consign the body
of the deceased to the earth,

1709
01:32:30,253 --> 01:32:33,839
"let us be mindful
of our own frailties
and mortality,

1710
01:32:33,924 --> 01:32:35,925
"that walking
always in Thy fear

1711
01:32:36,009 --> 01:32:38,219
"and in the ways
of Thy Commandments

1712
01:32:38,303 --> 01:32:40,304
"we may,
after our departure
from this world,

1713
01:32:40,388 --> 01:32:43,557
"experience
a merciful judgment

1714
01:32:43,642 --> 01:32:46,352
"and rejoice in
everlasting happiness

1715
01:32:46,686 --> 01:32:48,395
"through Christ, our Lord."

1716
01:32:48,480 --> 01:32:51,690
All them people
and the flowers,

1717
01:32:53,151 --> 01:32:56,195
some of them from people
I never heard of even.

1718
01:32:58,615 --> 01:33:00,574
Who would've thought
that many folks...

1719
01:33:01,952 --> 01:33:05,162
I mean,
they was carrying on

1720
01:33:05,247 --> 01:33:08,290
like they was
his family or, or...

1721
01:33:10,252 --> 01:33:11,418
I don't know.

1722
01:33:12,295 --> 01:33:17,174
Yeah. He took the time
to make a lot of people
love him, all right.

1723
01:33:17,801 --> 01:33:20,386
It's hard to figure out
so many of them showing up.

1724
01:33:22,681 --> 01:33:25,432
And they was
feeling something.

1725
01:33:27,394 --> 01:33:29,937
I mean,
there was no reason
for 'em to put on.

1726
01:33:30,855 --> 01:33:32,606
He was nobody big.
He was just a...

1727
01:33:32,691 --> 01:33:33,941
Katie.

1728
01:33:34,276 --> 01:33:35,901
Don't talk about
it no more, kid.

1729
01:33:46,329 --> 01:33:48,664
Francie.
Just leave her be, Katie.

1730
01:33:48,748 --> 01:33:49,957
She maybe wants
to be by herself.

1731
01:33:50,041 --> 01:33:51,125
She's taking on
kind of funny.

1732
01:33:51,209 --> 01:33:52,710
She ain't even cried.

1733
01:34:00,051 --> 01:34:01,343
Goodbye.

1734
01:34:10,186 --> 01:34:11,937
I'd like my
father's shaving cup.

1735
01:34:12,397 --> 01:34:13,814
That one. "Nolan."

1736
01:34:18,320 --> 01:34:20,404
Oh, you're the little girl.

1737
01:34:20,989 --> 01:34:22,865
Yes. I'll clean it
up for you.

1738
01:34:27,579 --> 01:34:28,912
He was a fine man.

1739
01:34:29,581 --> 01:34:32,458
Tell your mama
that I, his barber,
said this.

1740
01:35:13,291 --> 01:35:15,125
Francie.

1741
01:35:15,585 --> 01:35:16,877
What?

1742
01:35:19,297 --> 01:35:20,798
Francie, dear,
where are you going?

1743
01:35:22,634 --> 01:35:23,634
No place.

1744
01:35:25,970 --> 01:35:27,137
Francie.

1745
01:35:29,182 --> 01:35:30,182
Yes, Mama?

1746
01:35:31,351 --> 01:35:33,560
It was nice of the neighbors
to send over all that food.

1747
01:35:33,645 --> 01:35:34,978
Don't you want something?

1748
01:35:36,648 --> 01:35:37,731
No, Mama.

1749
01:35:40,360 --> 01:35:42,152
I wanted to talk
to you, Francie.

1750
01:35:43,571 --> 01:35:48,075
I want things to go on,
the reading and all.

1751
01:35:49,828 --> 01:35:50,828
I want to do...

1752
01:35:52,997 --> 01:35:55,791
Well, I got to be
mama and papa both
to you now, Francie.

1753
01:36:06,636 --> 01:36:08,220
Yes, Mama.
Is that all, Mama?

1754
01:36:10,932 --> 01:36:12,099
Well...

1755
01:36:15,228 --> 01:36:17,438
You gotta go right now,
Francie, I...

1756
01:36:17,522 --> 01:36:20,190
I'll be back.
Honest, I will.

1757
01:36:30,702 --> 01:36:31,827
Mom.

1758
01:36:34,038 --> 01:36:35,539
I guess
I'm a little hungry.

1759
01:36:39,836 --> 01:36:42,880
Look.
He can't be dead.
Can't!

1760
01:36:44,549 --> 01:36:45,883
They don't understand.

1761
01:36:49,888 --> 01:36:52,806
Maybe you could let me
have a baby someday,

1762
01:36:53,933 --> 01:36:55,434
and it could be a boy.

1763
01:36:56,311 --> 01:36:58,061
So it could be
just like him.

1764
01:37:00,732 --> 01:37:02,316
It would have to be me.

1765
01:37:03,651 --> 01:37:05,777
Nobody else
loved him like I do.

1766
01:37:08,781 --> 01:37:10,449
Maybe you could
do that for me.

1767
01:37:12,285 --> 01:37:13,702
And if you could,

1768
01:37:16,164 --> 01:37:18,665
he wouldn't even die.

1769
01:37:28,551 --> 01:37:31,428
I hope you don't think
I'm forward coming in
like this, Mrs. Nolan.

1770
01:37:32,305 --> 01:37:33,680
How are you, Francie?

1771
01:37:33,765 --> 01:37:34,932
I'm well, thank you.

1772
01:37:35,183 --> 01:37:38,519
Have a chair.
Francie, see if Mr. McGarrity
won't have some coffee.

1773
01:37:38,603 --> 01:37:40,062
Not for me,
thank you.

1774
01:37:40,563 --> 01:37:41,855
I figured
I ought to come.

1775
01:37:42,565 --> 01:37:44,441
I suppose you know
how Johnny and me
done business.

1776
01:37:45,443 --> 01:37:49,696
He'd give me some money
to keep sometimes
and draw against it.

1777
01:37:49,781 --> 01:37:51,532
And when he...

1778
01:37:51,616 --> 01:37:55,953
Well, I got
to looking around
and what do you think?

1779
01:37:57,247 --> 01:37:59,456
I had, I had nearly
five bucks in his box.

1780
01:38:00,416 --> 01:38:03,460
And so I,
I figured it
belonged to you.

1781
01:38:07,215 --> 01:38:08,590
If you told the truth,

1782
01:38:08,675 --> 01:38:10,676
it would be
more than likely
that he owed you.

1783
01:38:11,302 --> 01:38:14,680
But thanks very much.

1784
01:38:16,307 --> 01:38:17,975
Well, I just thought...

1785
01:38:18,059 --> 01:38:19,226
We'll make out.

1786
01:38:20,144 --> 01:38:22,104
Well, there's
something else then.

1787
01:38:23,064 --> 01:38:25,107
I thought maybe
you wouldn't mind

1788
01:38:25,567 --> 01:38:29,194
if maybe Francie
and Neeley came down
to work for me afternoons,

1789
01:38:29,279 --> 01:38:31,363
like, after school
and Saturdays.

1790
01:38:32,156 --> 01:38:34,283
And, of course,
maybe it ain't
the kind of a place

1791
01:38:34,367 --> 01:38:37,995
you'd favor them working in,
but I'd keep an eye on them.

1792
01:38:38,621 --> 01:38:41,373
And I'd pay them
$2 a week apiece.

1793
01:38:42,083 --> 01:38:45,460
And I'd take it as
a great favor, ma'am.

1794
01:38:48,131 --> 01:38:50,173
You're a very bad liar,
Mr. McGarrity,

1795
01:38:50,258 --> 01:38:55,053
but you're a good man,
and I'm ashamed
I didn't know it before.

1796
01:38:55,471 --> 01:38:57,264
No, it ain't
like that, ma'am.

1797
01:38:57,348 --> 01:39:00,350
Johnny was...
Well, I don't know.

1798
01:39:00,435 --> 01:39:03,895
Johnny...
Johnny always talked
about his family

1799
01:39:04,814 --> 01:39:07,274
like, well, like
folks ought to
and don't.

1800
01:39:07,984 --> 01:39:13,030
And, whenever
he talked about anything,
he always made you...

1801
01:39:13,948 --> 01:39:16,241
You felt better
or you wanted to laugh.

1802
01:39:17,410 --> 01:39:19,077
Like that seashell
I had there.

1803
01:39:19,537 --> 01:39:22,122
He was always,
he was always
listening to it

1804
01:39:22,206 --> 01:39:24,374
and telling you
what it was singing.

1805
01:39:26,169 --> 01:39:28,003
He was always
giving things
like that to people.

1806
01:39:28,963 --> 01:39:30,088
He...

1807
01:39:31,215 --> 01:39:33,342
He was a fine man,
Mrs. Nolan.

1808
01:39:39,057 --> 01:39:42,017
I'd be glad to let
the children work
for you, Mr. McGarrity.

1809
01:39:43,394 --> 01:39:46,688
And the $4 a week
will keep us
until the baby comes,

1810
01:39:46,773 --> 01:39:48,398
and Francie won't
have to quit school

1811
01:39:48,483 --> 01:39:50,150
and she can keep on,
and they can both...

1812
01:39:56,741 --> 01:39:58,700
Well, it's a deal then.
And you tell 'em

1813
01:39:58,785 --> 01:40:01,495
to come through
the family entrance
tomorrow after school.

1814
01:40:03,873 --> 01:40:05,749
Is that all right
with you, Francie?

1815
01:40:06,292 --> 01:40:08,085
Yes.

1816
01:40:09,420 --> 01:40:12,506
Well, well,
it's settled then

1817
01:40:12,590 --> 01:40:15,008
and, good day to you,
Mrs. Nolan.

1818
01:40:15,093 --> 01:40:17,177
And thank you again,
Mr. McGarrity.

1819
01:40:19,514 --> 01:40:21,598
Francie.
Yes, Mama.

1820
01:40:23,893 --> 01:40:26,311
I'm glad
you can keep on
with your school.

1821
01:40:26,938 --> 01:40:29,064
I was hoping
something like this
would happen,

1822
01:40:29,148 --> 01:40:32,275
but I didn't want
to say anything
until the time come.

1823
01:40:34,153 --> 01:40:36,571
But your papa and I
talked it all over

1824
01:40:36,656 --> 01:40:38,615
and there were reasons.

1825
01:40:39,826 --> 01:40:42,619
And there just
wasn't any other way.

1826
01:40:44,122 --> 01:40:47,874
It doesn't matter.
Papa saved me from it.

1827
01:41:04,308 --> 01:41:05,642
Hiya, kid.

1828
01:41:05,727 --> 01:41:06,977
Well, they're sure
taking chances.

1829
01:41:07,061 --> 01:41:08,770
I wouldn't,
leaving you handle
them eats.

1830
01:41:08,855 --> 01:41:10,689
- Where's Francie?
-  Kitchen.

1831
01:41:10,773 --> 01:41:12,858
Thanks. Hiya, Mac.

1832
01:41:12,984 --> 01:41:14,693
Hello, kid.
How are you, lamb?
Hello, Aunt Sissy.

1833
01:41:14,777 --> 01:41:16,445
Look. You got to
do something for me.

1834
01:41:16,571 --> 01:41:18,238
This was in the paper,
and I cut it out.

1835
01:41:18,322 --> 01:41:21,783
You got to
read it to me, and...
What's the matter, hon?

1836
01:41:21,909 --> 01:41:24,453
Nothing. I'm all right,
Aunt Sissy.
No, you ain't.

1837
01:41:24,537 --> 01:41:25,829
You ain't been since...

1838
01:41:25,913 --> 01:41:28,749
Look. Don't you think
you better spill it
to your Aunt Sissy?

1839
01:41:28,833 --> 01:41:30,959
What is it
you want me to read
to you, Aunt Sissy?

1840
01:41:31,043 --> 01:41:33,003
Well, we'll get that
out of the way first.

1841
01:41:33,087 --> 01:41:34,963
Look. Here it is.
Likely you don't
remember him.

1842
01:41:35,047 --> 01:41:36,548
But it's my
last husband, Bill.

1843
01:41:36,632 --> 01:41:38,258
The one
I thought was dead,
but he ain't.

1844
01:41:38,342 --> 01:41:39,426
He's got his picture
in there,

1845
01:41:39,510 --> 01:41:40,594
and I wanna know
what it says.

1846
01:41:40,678 --> 01:41:42,304
Maybe it says where he lives
so as I can write to him

1847
01:41:42,388 --> 01:41:44,055
about getting a divorce
or something.

1848
01:41:44,140 --> 01:41:45,932
I got the best husband
in all the world now

1849
01:41:46,017 --> 01:41:48,185
and I don't want this
here one bobbing up
and making no trouble.

1850
01:41:48,644 --> 01:41:50,812
He's a fireman someplace.
I can tell that
from his clothes.

1851
01:41:50,897 --> 01:41:52,272
He was just starting out
in the fireman business...

1852
01:41:52,356 --> 01:41:54,775
This says he's a hero.
He saved some people
in a fire.

1853
01:41:54,859 --> 01:41:56,401
Does it say where?

1854
01:41:56,486 --> 01:41:58,236
The 9th Precinct,
Manhattan.

1855
01:41:58,321 --> 01:41:59,571
Manhattan, huh?

1856
01:41:59,655 --> 01:42:01,782
Couldn't make the grade
in Brooklyn, I guess.

1857
01:42:01,866 --> 01:42:04,117
I want you to
write to him, Francie.
Write this,

1858
01:42:04,202 --> 01:42:05,452
"Dear Bill..."

1859
01:42:05,536 --> 01:42:07,621
This says his name
is Roland Polaski.

1860
01:42:07,705 --> 01:42:09,790
That's right,
I remember.

1861
01:42:09,874 --> 01:42:12,125
Make it
"Dear Mr. Polaski.

1862
01:42:12,210 --> 01:42:14,252
"Being's as now I'm married
to somebody else

1863
01:42:14,337 --> 01:42:17,088
"I want you
to see about getting
a real legal divorce

1864
01:42:17,173 --> 01:42:19,549
"because I thought
you was dead,
but you ain't.

1865
01:42:19,634 --> 01:42:22,010
"And because
you got the money now
on account of the reward.

1866
01:42:22,094 --> 01:42:23,970
"Yours very truly, Sissy."
Something like that.

1867
01:42:24,055 --> 01:42:26,306
But, Aunt Sissy,
he must have
already done that.

1868
01:42:26,390 --> 01:42:28,099
Because it says here
he's married again.

1869
01:42:28,768 --> 01:42:30,143
It does?

1870
01:42:30,228 --> 01:42:31,812
"On the human interest
side of the story,

1871
01:42:31,896 --> 01:42:34,898
"Mrs. Polaski had returned
home only the day before
from the hospital

1872
01:42:34,982 --> 01:42:37,734
"after presenting Mr. Polaski
with a brand-new son,

1873
01:42:37,819 --> 01:42:39,528
"the fourth child
of the marriage."

1874
01:42:39,612 --> 01:42:42,322
So, if he got a divorce
that long ago,
you don't have to.

1875
01:42:42,406 --> 01:42:43,824
Then my being
married to Bill,

1876
01:42:43,908 --> 01:42:45,242
this one, I mean,
is all legal?

1877
01:42:46,077 --> 01:42:49,037
Well, now,
if that ain't a load
off my chest.

1878
01:42:49,121 --> 01:42:52,541
You know something?
I think I'll give Bill Polaski
a wedding present.

1879
01:42:52,625 --> 01:42:55,460
But Aunt Sissy, you can't.
He's been married for years.

1880
01:42:56,254 --> 01:43:00,382
Four kids, huh?
Must be a pretty sickly woman,
this Mrs. Polaski,

1881
01:43:00,466 --> 01:43:02,509
going to the hospital
just to have a baby.

1882
01:43:02,593 --> 01:43:04,845
No. Lots of people
go there now
to have babies.

1883
01:43:04,929 --> 01:43:06,012
It's better.

1884
01:43:06,097 --> 01:43:09,182
Sure enough?
You know something?

1885
01:43:09,934 --> 01:43:11,393
I'm gonna cash in
my funeral policy

1886
01:43:11,477 --> 01:43:12,936
and have my baby
at a hospital.

1887
01:43:13,563 --> 01:43:15,939
And when my baby
is born and lives,

1888
01:43:16,816 --> 01:43:19,526
I want you to write
that R. Polaski
and announce it.

1889
01:43:19,610 --> 01:43:21,319
Boy, do I feel better!

1890
01:43:21,404 --> 01:43:23,280
And, now, chickabiddy,
we'll talk about you.

1891
01:43:23,406 --> 01:43:25,490
Can't your Aunt Sissy
help you any?
I'm all right.

1892
01:43:25,575 --> 01:43:27,742
No, you aren't, honey,
not all shut up
like that.

1893
01:43:27,827 --> 01:43:29,911
I know how you feel,
but you can't keep
hanging on to it.

1894
01:43:29,996 --> 01:43:32,038
I'm all right.
I don't want to
talk about it.

1895
01:43:32,874 --> 01:43:34,916
All right, baby.
All right.

1896
01:43:35,001 --> 01:43:37,502
But I'll tell you what.
You can do
something for me.

1897
01:43:38,254 --> 01:43:41,131
Look.
Your mama feels
awful bad, too.

1898
01:43:42,008 --> 01:43:44,718
She needs you.
Why don't you talk
to her about it?

1899
01:43:44,802 --> 01:43:46,094
She doesn't need me.
Yes, she does.

1900
01:43:46,178 --> 01:43:47,512
No, she doesn't!
She's got Neeley!

1901
01:43:47,597 --> 01:43:49,222
Why wasn't it Neeley
she was going to
make quit school?

1902
01:43:49,307 --> 01:43:50,682
He never
cared about it.

1903
01:43:50,766 --> 01:43:52,434
She doesn't love me
like Papa did,

1904
01:43:52,518 --> 01:43:54,686
and she didn't
love him, either.
Not really.

1905
01:43:54,770 --> 01:43:58,064
She hurt him. I saw her.
And he never hurt anybody.

1906
01:43:58,149 --> 01:44:00,317
I'm gonna finish this grade
because he gave it to me.

1907
01:44:00,401 --> 01:44:03,194
And then I'll work for her,
but she can't be Papa to me.

1908
01:44:03,279 --> 01:44:04,404
She can't ever!

1909
01:44:04,488 --> 01:44:05,864
Don't be like that,
baby. Don't.

1910
01:44:05,948 --> 01:44:08,241
Leave me alone.
I'm all right.

1911
01:44:08,326 --> 01:44:10,619
Please go away
and leave me alone.

1912
01:44:12,997 --> 01:44:15,916
All right, chickabiddy.
All right.

1913
01:44:23,341 --> 01:44:25,342
Mr. Stern.
Yes, sir.

1914
01:44:31,223 --> 01:44:34,184
Francie.
Yes, Mama?

1915
01:44:37,355 --> 01:44:38,688
I want to talk
to you, Francie.

1916
01:44:43,861 --> 01:44:45,195
Yes, Mama.

1917
01:44:45,529 --> 01:44:46,905
It isn't gonna be
long now,

1918
01:44:47,657 --> 01:44:49,866
for me, I mean,
my baby.

1919
01:44:51,160 --> 01:44:52,577
We can't come
to a hospital.

1920
01:44:53,287 --> 01:44:56,206
There isn't even
gonna be enough money
for a woman to come and help.

1921
01:44:58,459 --> 01:44:59,876
I'm gonna
need you, Francie.

1922
01:45:02,421 --> 01:45:04,839
Don't ever be far away.
Neeley's...

1923
01:45:05,466 --> 01:45:07,884
Well, a boy ain't much good
at a time like this.

1924
01:45:09,053 --> 01:45:10,261
I'm counting
on you, Francie.

1925
01:45:11,555 --> 01:45:12,889
You won't forget that,
will you?

1926
01:45:14,558 --> 01:45:17,435
All right, Mama.
I'll remember.

1927
01:45:18,312 --> 01:45:20,021
Which one of you
is Mr. Stephen Edwards?

1928
01:45:20,439 --> 01:45:21,773
That's me.

1929
01:45:22,191 --> 01:45:23,733
Well, there are three
in your family now.

1930
01:45:23,818 --> 01:45:25,276
You're the father
of a pretty fine boy.

1931
01:45:25,361 --> 01:45:27,028
Alive?
Very much so.

1932
01:45:27,113 --> 01:45:28,780
He was a little reluctant
about it at first.

1933
01:45:28,864 --> 01:45:31,324
I had to rouse him
with a little oxygen.
Now, he's mad at me.

1934
01:45:31,409 --> 01:45:33,410
You ought to hear him.
I've got to see him.

1935
01:45:33,494 --> 01:45:36,246
Well, neither one of them
are quite up to a visit
just now.

1936
01:45:36,330 --> 01:45:37,664
In a little while.

1937
01:45:37,832 --> 01:45:39,124
The learning...

1938
01:45:39,208 --> 01:45:41,835
The learning that
saved that baby.

1939
01:45:41,919 --> 01:45:44,045
That's fine, Bill.

1940
01:45:44,130 --> 01:45:45,880
Where are you going,
Uncle Bill?

1941
01:45:45,965 --> 01:45:49,009
I'm going out and get
some strawberry ice cream
and a rattle for my son.

1942
01:45:49,093 --> 01:45:52,012
And what's more,
my name ain't Bill.
It's Steve.

1943
01:45:52,096 --> 01:45:54,764
Do you hear that?
I'm a papa,
and my name's Steve.

1944
01:45:54,849 --> 01:45:56,808
And it's Uncle Steve, too.

1945
01:45:57,226 --> 01:46:00,270
Steve. Steve. Steve.

1946
01:46:00,896 --> 01:46:03,064
So, we have a man
in the family.

1947
01:46:10,448 --> 01:46:12,574
As quick as we see
if she's all right,
you go on up to McGarrity's

1948
01:46:12,658 --> 01:46:14,325
and see if you can
do my work, too.

1949
01:46:14,410 --> 01:46:17,370
I'm gonna finish
her scrubbing for her.
She ought not to do any more.

1950
01:46:17,455 --> 01:46:19,622
She wasn't feeling
good this morning.

1951
01:46:23,252 --> 01:46:24,419
Mama!

1952
01:46:31,802 --> 01:46:33,136
Mama?

1953
01:46:33,679 --> 01:46:34,846
In here, Francie.

1954
01:46:37,975 --> 01:46:39,350
You wait here.

1955
01:46:42,688 --> 01:46:43,980
You all right, Mama?

1956
01:46:49,779 --> 01:46:52,989
Give Neeley a nickel
to go after
Grandma and Sissy.

1957
01:46:54,075 --> 01:46:56,201
He can walk home after.

1958
01:46:56,285 --> 01:46:58,203
Get me a nightgown
in that bottom drawer.

1959
01:47:05,669 --> 01:47:07,670
Hurry! Don't stand
there staring.

1960
01:47:16,013 --> 01:47:17,138
Is she going to die?

1961
01:47:17,223 --> 01:47:18,348
Of course not.
It's the baby.

1962
01:47:18,432 --> 01:47:20,266
You heard
what Mama said,
and hurry.

1963
01:47:20,351 --> 01:47:22,727
And don't forget
stopping at McGarrity's
on the way back.

1964
01:47:22,812 --> 01:47:26,314
We can't lose the work.
She only wants me now.

1965
01:47:34,532 --> 01:47:35,698
Mama!

1966
01:47:36,408 --> 01:47:37,575
What is it?

1967
01:47:38,327 --> 01:47:40,370
I'll be there
in a minute.

1968
01:48:07,064 --> 01:48:09,357
You're taking
real good care
of me, Francie.

1969
01:48:10,651 --> 01:48:11,734
Am I, Mama?

1970
01:48:22,079 --> 01:48:23,371
Mmm.

1971
01:48:26,000 --> 01:48:27,208
Tastes good.

1972
01:48:36,844 --> 01:48:39,012
Can I get you
a glass of water, Mama?

1973
01:48:39,096 --> 01:48:41,181
When I want something,
I'll ask for it.

1974
01:48:42,099 --> 01:48:43,433
Yes, Mama.

1975
01:48:44,727 --> 01:48:48,271
Don't just stand there
and throw questions at me.
I'm too tired.

1976
01:48:49,607 --> 01:48:51,399
You'd better have
some coffee, too.

1977
01:48:51,483 --> 01:48:53,276
Mama, even if
Neeley is a boy,

1978
01:48:53,360 --> 01:48:54,777
wouldn't you rather
have him here?

1979
01:48:54,862 --> 01:48:56,112
He's always such
a comfort to you.

1980
01:48:56,197 --> 01:48:58,531
No, it's you
that's a comfort.
Now, what time is it?

1981
01:48:58,616 --> 01:49:00,617
I don't know, Mama.
Get the clock.

1982
01:49:10,794 --> 01:49:12,420
One minute
to 4:00, Mama.

1983
01:49:12,922 --> 01:49:14,464
Are you sure
it isn't slow?

1984
01:49:14,965 --> 01:49:16,299
No, Mama.

1985
01:49:16,967 --> 01:49:18,468
Maybe it's fast then.

1986
01:49:19,887 --> 01:49:22,180
I'll look at
the jeweler's clock
out the parlor window!

1987
01:49:27,853 --> 01:49:31,606
The candle's pretty
like Christmas.

1988
01:49:35,110 --> 01:49:36,903
That was the night
I told him.

1989
01:49:45,204 --> 01:49:47,622
It's nice having a visit
from my daughter.

1990
01:49:50,584 --> 01:49:53,169
I didn't want for you
to have to grow up
so soon.

1991
01:49:54,296 --> 01:49:56,756
I didn't want for you
to have to quit school.

1992
01:49:56,840 --> 01:49:59,759
I tried to tell him that.
He didn't mind about the baby

1993
01:49:59,843 --> 01:50:02,720
but he never forgive me
for wanting you
to quit school.

1994
01:50:03,681 --> 01:50:06,849
I told him,
and he just went out.

1995
01:50:08,602 --> 01:50:09,936
You never
forgive me, either.

1996
01:50:10,020 --> 01:50:11,187
Please don't, Mama.

1997
01:50:11,272 --> 01:50:13,690
He would've
bought you dolls
instead of milk, and...

1998
01:50:13,774 --> 01:50:15,358
I don't know.
Maybe you would've
been happier.

1999
01:50:15,442 --> 01:50:16,484
I don't know.

2000
01:50:16,568 --> 01:50:20,029
I never would've
thought of giving you
that school like he did.

2001
01:50:20,114 --> 01:50:22,407
And all them
fine compositions
of yours,

2002
01:50:23,409 --> 01:50:25,076
I never read one of 'em.

2003
01:50:25,160 --> 01:50:27,996
I should've had time.
Johnny did.

2004
01:50:28,080 --> 01:50:29,914
But I couldn't
do no different.

2005
01:50:29,999 --> 01:50:32,000
I don't know
how I could do
any different.

2006
01:50:39,550 --> 01:50:40,591
What time is it?

2007
01:50:42,011 --> 01:50:43,845
One minute
after 4:00, Mama.

2008
01:50:45,389 --> 01:50:48,099
Wring a cloth
out of cold water
and wipe my face.

2009
01:51:00,571 --> 01:51:02,530
Don't let her die.
Please!

2010
01:51:18,464 --> 01:51:22,258
Mama, suppose the baby
comes before Grandma
and Aunt Sissy get here?

2011
01:51:22,926 --> 01:51:25,219
You can see I couldn't
do no different, can't you?

2012
01:51:26,638 --> 01:51:30,391
Neeley, he don't like school.
If he'd quit,
he'd never go back again.

2013
01:51:31,226 --> 01:51:33,686
But you,
no matter what happens,
you'd find a way to go back.

2014
01:51:33,771 --> 01:51:37,023
You'd fight to go back.
You can see that, can't you?

2015
01:51:38,359 --> 01:51:39,525
I...

2016
01:51:41,278 --> 01:51:42,362
Yes, Mama.

2017
01:51:43,947 --> 01:51:45,281
Read me something,
Francie.

2018
01:51:45,616 --> 01:51:46,949
Yes, Mama.

2019
01:51:47,701 --> 01:51:49,243
Read me one of
your compositions.

2020
01:51:49,328 --> 01:51:51,621
I ain't never read any
of your compositions.

2021
01:51:51,789 --> 01:51:53,122
It's on my conscience.

2022
01:51:58,879 --> 01:52:00,380
I tore all those up.

2023
01:52:00,923 --> 01:52:02,465
No, you didn't.

2024
01:52:03,008 --> 01:52:04,133
Not all of them.

2025
01:52:06,595 --> 01:52:09,472
Can't I read
you Shakespeare?
It's much better.

2026
01:52:11,141 --> 01:52:12,767
Read "'Twas on
a Night Like This."

2027
01:52:13,185 --> 01:52:15,395
I'd like to have something
pretty on my mind.

2028
01:52:16,313 --> 01:52:17,647
Sit by the candle.

2029
01:52:27,616 --> 01:52:30,785
"The moon shines bright
in such a night as this

2030
01:52:30,869 --> 01:52:33,121
"when the sweet wind
did gently kiss the trees."

2031
01:52:33,205 --> 01:52:36,582
Say, did you ever find out
who Troilus was and Cressida?

2032
01:52:36,667 --> 01:52:38,126
Yes, Mama. Troilus was...

2033
01:52:38,210 --> 01:52:40,294
Some other day
when I've got time.

2034
01:52:40,379 --> 01:52:42,505
Read me one of
your compositions now.

2035
01:52:43,006 --> 01:52:44,132
You won't like them, Mama.

2036
01:52:44,216 --> 01:52:45,925
You thought about 'em,
and you worked on 'em

2037
01:52:46,009 --> 01:52:47,635
and you got
good marks on 'em.

2038
01:52:48,262 --> 01:52:49,345
Get 'em, I said.

2039
01:53:23,380 --> 01:53:24,464
Sit here.

2040
01:53:29,011 --> 01:53:30,136
Go on.

2041
01:53:33,307 --> 01:53:37,018
It's called
"The Man People Loved."

2042
01:53:39,396 --> 01:53:41,063
Please don't make me
read it, Mama.

2043
01:53:41,148 --> 01:53:42,440
Read it.

2044
01:53:45,903 --> 01:53:51,073
"Perhaps many people
might have said of him
that he was a failure.

2045
01:53:51,867 --> 01:53:54,327
"It is true
that he had no gift
for making money,

2046
01:53:55,037 --> 01:53:56,954
"but he had a gift
for laughter

2047
01:53:57,039 --> 01:53:58,831
"and for making
people love him.

2048
01:53:59,583 --> 01:54:01,501
"He had the gift of
making you feel proud

2049
01:54:01,585 --> 01:54:03,336
"to walk down
the street with him.

2050
01:54:04,087 --> 01:54:05,963
"He had nothing to
give but himself,

2051
01:54:06,548 --> 01:54:09,425
"but of this
he gave generously,
like a king."

2052
01:54:09,510 --> 01:54:13,763
"Like a king."
That's like it was.

2053
01:54:14,598 --> 01:54:17,558
Walking down
the street with him,
you always felt like that.

2054
01:54:18,644 --> 01:54:19,810
Did you, Mama?

2055
01:54:20,687 --> 01:54:23,689
You're real smart
to write it down
like that, Francie.

2056
01:54:23,774 --> 01:54:25,066
That's like it was.

2057
01:54:27,027 --> 01:54:28,444
Francie.

2058
01:54:31,281 --> 01:54:33,282
I miss him so much.

2059
01:54:36,620 --> 01:54:38,996
If the baby's a boy,
we'll call him Johnny.

2060
01:54:39,540 --> 01:54:43,501
Where's Sissy?
Neeley's been gone
a long time.

2061
01:54:47,047 --> 01:54:48,422
Wipe my face.

2062
01:54:48,507 --> 01:54:50,299
No, don't let go
of my hand.

2063
01:54:51,969 --> 01:54:56,347
If it's a girl,
we'll call her
Annie Laurie.

2064
01:54:56,431 --> 01:54:58,349
Remember that tune
he played?

2065
01:54:58,934 --> 01:55:03,145
You ought to
have piano lessons.
I'll see if I can manage.

2066
01:55:03,230 --> 01:55:06,440
You won't forget
to dust the piano,
will you, Francie?

2067
01:55:07,025 --> 01:55:09,402
Who'd cry for me
like that if I died?

2068
01:55:09,486 --> 01:55:12,363
I never did
a wrong thing in my life,
but it ain't enough!

2069
01:55:12,447 --> 01:55:17,326
Sissy,
I didn't mean to be hard
like you said.

2070
01:55:17,869 --> 01:55:19,370
If Johnny was here,

2071
01:55:19,454 --> 01:55:22,039
he could go
to your graduation,
and I'd go to Neeley's.

2072
01:55:22,124 --> 01:55:26,502
But I can't tear myself
into two pieces.

2073
01:55:26,962 --> 01:55:28,462
How am I gonna do both?

2074
01:55:31,883 --> 01:55:33,551
Where are you, Francie?

2075
01:55:33,635 --> 01:55:35,011
I'm here, Mama!

2076
01:55:38,849 --> 01:55:40,516
You're such
a comfort to me.

2077
01:55:42,019 --> 01:55:43,185
I'm so tired.

2078
01:55:45,147 --> 01:55:46,689
Leave me sleep now.

2079
01:56:01,955 --> 01:56:03,706
You better start
some water boiling.

2080
01:56:03,790 --> 01:56:05,374
We'll call you
if there's anything
we need.

2081
01:56:05,459 --> 01:56:07,001
I thought
you was never
coming, Sissy.

2082
01:56:07,210 --> 01:56:09,670
Come on.
You quit worrying now.

2083
01:56:35,405 --> 01:56:39,325
The baby is here
and the mama
is doing good.

2084
01:56:39,743 --> 01:56:40,993
She's asleep.

2085
01:56:41,453 --> 01:56:43,788
A small baby sister,
it is.

2086
01:56:50,545 --> 01:56:51,921
Annie Laurie.

2087
01:56:53,590 --> 01:56:55,091
Papa would've
liked that.

2088
01:57:01,640 --> 01:57:04,016
Look, Francie.
Aren't the flowers pretty?

2089
01:57:07,270 --> 01:57:08,979
Where's Grandma?

2090
01:57:09,064 --> 01:57:10,940
I got her in a front seat,
so she won't miss a thing.

2091
01:57:12,150 --> 01:57:14,235
Isn't your classroom
around here somewheres?

2092
01:57:14,319 --> 01:57:15,361
Yes, but I...

2093
01:57:15,487 --> 01:57:16,529
How about
giving me a peek?

2094
01:57:16,613 --> 01:57:18,864
Wouldn't hurt me none,
seeing a little
more places like that.

2095
01:57:23,704 --> 01:57:26,163
Hey, Francie,
you forgot your flowers.
They aren't mine.

2096
01:57:26,248 --> 01:57:28,249
I'm not carrying
flowers today.

2097
01:57:28,333 --> 01:57:30,668
Some of the girls,
their family
sends them flowers.

2098
01:57:30,752 --> 01:57:33,462
They're on your desk, lamb.
Better go see.

2099
01:57:36,466 --> 01:57:39,301
Well, I have to
get my things anyway.

2100
01:58:13,837 --> 01:58:15,880
He gave me
the money to buy 'em
way before Christmas

2101
01:58:17,174 --> 01:58:18,507
to make sure
he had it, he said.

2102
01:58:19,760 --> 01:58:20,926
Then he wrote out the card.

2103
01:58:32,355 --> 01:58:33,439
Come on, kid.

2104
01:58:36,526 --> 01:58:39,945
Let it go, baby.
There ain't a soul
gonna hear. Let it go.

2105
01:58:49,539 --> 01:58:51,081
Frances Nolan.

2106
01:59:02,886 --> 01:59:05,971
Well, sir,
I don't think Grandma said
one word the whole time.

2107
01:59:06,056 --> 01:59:07,932
And from the looks of her
when I put her on
the streetcar,

2108
01:59:08,016 --> 01:59:09,975
she'll probably
ride clear out to
Coney Island

2109
01:59:10,060 --> 01:59:11,769
and never know
the difference.

2110
01:59:12,103 --> 01:59:13,437
Heaven knows what
she'd have been like

2111
01:59:13,522 --> 01:59:15,606
if she'd got to
both graduations.

2112
01:59:15,690 --> 01:59:19,068
Looks to me like
it was a pretty fine day.
How's your soda, Francie?

2113
01:59:19,152 --> 01:59:20,611
Pineapple's not as
good as chocolate.

2114
01:59:20,737 --> 01:59:22,238
Then why did you
order it for?

2115
01:59:22,322 --> 01:59:24,573
Because I'm up to the "P's."
I'll try raspberry next.

2116
01:59:24,658 --> 01:59:26,116
There's something
to that idea.

2117
01:59:26,201 --> 01:59:27,159
Try everything once.

2118
01:59:27,244 --> 01:59:28,327
Sissy!

2119
01:59:28,411 --> 01:59:31,330
And a dime for you, my boy.
This is a special occasion.

2120
01:59:31,414 --> 01:59:32,373
Thank you.

2121
01:59:32,457 --> 01:59:33,582
He don't know
how special it is.

2122
01:59:33,750 --> 01:59:34,875
Two diplomas in
the Nolan family

2123
01:59:34,960 --> 01:59:36,126
all in one day?

2124
01:59:36,211 --> 01:59:39,046
Mama, I've got a nickel
if you want to leave it.

2125
01:59:39,130 --> 01:59:40,589
People do.

2126
01:59:40,674 --> 01:59:43,008
It's going to be
all right, Francie.

2127
01:59:43,093 --> 01:59:46,262
And you know somethin'?
These ain't gonna be
the last diplomas, either.

2128
01:59:46,346 --> 01:59:47,513
I don't know how
we're gonna work it,

2129
01:59:47,597 --> 01:59:49,890
but we're gonna find
some way for you and...

2130
01:59:49,975 --> 01:59:51,976
Hi, Neeley.
How are you doing?

2131
01:59:52,060 --> 01:59:54,478
Okay. I got out of jail.

2132
01:59:54,563 --> 01:59:56,856
Say, wasn't it you
I saw working

2133
01:59:56,940 --> 01:59:58,649
behind that bat
the other day?

2134
01:59:58,733 --> 01:59:59,817
Why, yeah, but...

2135
01:59:59,901 --> 02:00:01,193
Hey, you were
pretty good.

2136
02:00:01,278 --> 02:00:04,321
You know what?
I'm coming out and give you
some pointers sometime.

2137
02:00:04,406 --> 02:00:06,240
Honest?
Sure, I will.

2138
02:00:06,324 --> 02:00:07,992
That is, if your ma
don't mind.

2139
02:00:08,076 --> 02:00:09,660
Nah, she don't mind.

2140
02:00:09,744 --> 02:00:11,412
Ya mean it?
Sure.

2141
02:00:13,039 --> 02:00:15,291
Well, I'll see you
on the lot.

2142
02:00:16,626 --> 02:00:18,252
Maybe you better
ask your ma, you know.

2143
02:00:18,336 --> 02:00:20,546
I don't want to do anything
she wouldn't want me to.

2144
02:00:20,630 --> 02:00:21,922
Nah, she won't care.

2145
02:00:22,007 --> 02:00:24,717
Maybe you'd better ask her
yourself just to make sure.

2146
02:00:24,801 --> 02:00:27,469
I'm Neeley's aunt.
This is his ma.

2147
02:00:28,263 --> 02:00:31,724
But that's his sister.
What's your name,
big boy?

2148
02:00:31,933 --> 02:00:33,017
Herschel Knutsen.

2149
02:00:33,101 --> 02:00:35,895
Mr. Knutsen,
I'd like for you
to meet my niece,

2150
02:00:35,979 --> 02:00:37,771
Miss Francie Nolan.

2151
02:00:39,441 --> 02:00:40,566
Pleased to meet you.

2152
02:00:40,984 --> 02:00:42,151
Hello.

2153
02:00:44,779 --> 02:00:47,990
Nice night if it don't rain.
Sit down, Herschel.

2154
02:00:53,663 --> 02:00:55,831
Doing anything
tomorrow afternoon,
Miss Nolan?

2155
02:00:55,916 --> 02:00:57,124
It's Saturday.

2156
02:00:57,208 --> 02:00:59,460
I don't know. Why?

2157
02:00:59,544 --> 02:01:04,089
Well, there's
a swell picture, Bill Hart.
Maybe you'd like to go.

2158
02:01:04,174 --> 02:01:05,257
Who with?

2159
02:01:05,342 --> 02:01:06,550
Me.

2160
02:01:07,010 --> 02:01:08,260
Oh.

2161
02:01:15,977 --> 02:01:19,730
Well, I might be busy.
I'll let you know.

2162
02:01:19,814 --> 02:01:21,899
Well, I'll come
around and see.

2163
02:01:21,983 --> 02:01:24,652
Hey! I thought
we was gonna
play ball tomorrow.

2164
02:01:24,736 --> 02:01:26,779
Yeah. Well, we can
do that any time.

2165
02:01:26,863 --> 02:01:28,155
Sure.
There's lots of time.

2166
02:01:28,239 --> 02:01:29,782
Come on, Hersch.

2167
02:01:29,866 --> 02:01:32,451
Well, I'll be
seeing you,
Miss Nolan.

2168
02:01:35,914 --> 02:01:37,289
Him, mushy!

2169
02:01:37,666 --> 02:01:40,125
I'm proud of you,
chickabiddy.
You handled him fine.

2170
02:01:40,210 --> 02:01:41,877
It was the hair
that done it.

2171
02:01:41,962 --> 02:01:43,796
Well, I hate to
bust this party up,

2172
02:01:43,880 --> 02:01:45,255
but then babies
got to be fed.

2173
02:01:45,340 --> 02:01:47,383
Steve will be needin'
a little something, too.

2174
02:01:47,467 --> 02:01:49,760
Three hours with
the both of them.

2175
02:01:49,844 --> 02:01:51,553
Thirty out of 50.
Keep the change.

2176
02:01:52,180 --> 02:01:55,015
Well, thank you.
Why, Katie Nolan!

2177
02:01:55,100 --> 02:01:56,558
I don't care.

2178
02:01:57,185 --> 02:01:59,019
There's times
when feelin' good

2179
02:01:59,104 --> 02:02:01,230
and things like that
is important.

2180
02:02:01,314 --> 02:02:02,773
I don't care.

2181
02:02:09,239 --> 02:02:11,657
You wanna carry
my flowers, Mama?

2182
02:02:23,128 --> 02:02:25,004
He called ya
"Miss Nolan."

2183
02:02:25,088 --> 02:02:26,880
You missed it, Steve!

2184
02:02:26,965 --> 02:02:29,174
Well, hello, handsome.

2185
02:02:29,300 --> 02:02:31,510
I'm beggin' your pardon,
Mrs. Nolan.

2186
02:02:31,594 --> 02:02:32,970
I just happened to drop in,

2187
02:02:33,054 --> 02:02:36,640
and your brother-in-law here
seemed to be needing
a little help.

2188
02:02:36,725 --> 02:02:40,769
And the baby
didn't seem to mind, so...
I hope I'm not intrudin'.

2189
02:02:41,646 --> 02:02:44,023
Well, not at all,
Mr. McShane.

2190
02:02:47,152 --> 02:02:51,989
You sit right down.
We're going home.
Come along, Steve.

2191
02:02:55,160 --> 02:02:56,744
I'll take her,
Mr. McShane.

2192
02:02:56,828 --> 02:02:58,662
I'd like it
if you'd leave her.

2193
02:02:58,747 --> 02:03:01,457
Her and me has got
to be good friends.

2194
02:03:04,794 --> 02:03:06,253
Well, I wish you
didn't have to hurry.

2195
02:03:06,337 --> 02:03:08,297
Got to get this
family of mine home.

2196
02:03:08,381 --> 02:03:13,093
Steve's got to deliver milk
to a lot of those babies
that like that bottled kind.

2197
02:03:13,178 --> 02:03:15,804
You don't want to
frown like that, Katie.

2198
02:03:16,556 --> 02:03:18,599
The fellas don't go
for that at all.

2199
02:03:18,683 --> 02:03:20,768
Goodbye, kids.
So long, Mac.

2200
02:03:21,144 --> 02:03:22,936
So long, Mrs. Edwards.

2201
02:03:23,021 --> 02:03:24,980
Thank you, Aunt Sissy.

2202
02:03:28,485 --> 02:03:29,485
Goodbye, Mac.

2203
02:03:29,569 --> 02:03:30,819
Mr. Edwards, goodbye.

2204
02:03:34,657 --> 02:03:35,824
Well...

2205
02:03:37,368 --> 02:03:40,537
Well, I will take
the baby from you,
Mr. McShane.

2206
02:03:48,588 --> 02:03:49,963
Mrs. Nolan.

2207
02:03:53,009 --> 02:03:56,345
Likely you've been wonderin'
why I came here tonight.

2208
02:03:57,972 --> 02:04:01,600
Let your wonderin' be over,
because I came here
on a personal matter.

2209
02:04:01,684 --> 02:04:03,018
Mama, shall I go and...

2210
02:04:03,103 --> 02:04:05,479
No, no, don't be
leaving, children.

2211
02:04:05,563 --> 02:04:09,858
My conversation
will be concernin' you
as well as your mother.

2212
02:04:14,739 --> 02:04:18,909
Mrs. Nolan, I feel that
there's no disrespect

2213
02:04:18,993 --> 02:04:20,869
in my speaking
my mind at this time.

2214
02:04:21,621 --> 02:04:25,290
And I feel
a decent time
has elapsed

2215
02:04:25,708 --> 02:04:29,878
since the passin'
of Mrs. McShane,
God rest her soul.

2216
02:04:31,714 --> 02:04:34,133
I didn't know,
Mr. McShane.

2217
02:04:34,217 --> 02:04:35,300
I'm sorry.

2218
02:04:35,385 --> 02:04:36,969
Well, I said nothin',
Mrs. Nolan,

2219
02:04:37,053 --> 02:04:39,847
because it was
near the time of
your own bereavement.

2220
02:04:39,931 --> 02:04:42,057
And I didn't wish to...

2221
02:04:42,142 --> 02:04:44,768
Well, I know
that it's barely
six months now

2222
02:04:44,853 --> 02:04:50,149
since your own husband,
too, left this world.
Rest his soul.

2223
02:04:51,776 --> 02:04:56,155
But when you feel
a decent interval
has elapsed,

2224
02:04:57,073 --> 02:05:00,200
I'm askin' to keep
company with you,
Katherine Nolan,

2225
02:05:00,285 --> 02:05:05,122
with the object of a weddin'
when a decent time
has elapsed.

2226
02:05:08,501 --> 02:05:10,085
And for my part,

2227
02:05:11,796 --> 02:05:14,423
I'll be glad to
keep company with you,
Mr. McShane,

2228
02:05:15,466 --> 02:05:18,177
not for the help
you can give us,

2229
02:05:18,261 --> 02:05:21,138
because we know
we can manage some way.

2230
02:05:21,222 --> 02:05:25,517
But because
you're a good man,
Mr. McShane.

2231
02:05:31,774 --> 02:05:36,486
And there's
one more thing.

2232
02:05:37,822 --> 02:05:43,535
Their father was a fine man,
and I'd have no wish to be
tryin' to take his place.

2233
02:05:44,454 --> 02:05:50,500
It would be more
my intention to be
like a real good friend.

2234
02:05:51,461 --> 02:05:55,130
Now, as the eldest,
would you be approvin'?

2235
02:05:59,427 --> 02:06:00,969
Yes, Mr. McShane.

2236
02:06:05,475 --> 02:06:08,477
I was thinkin' it
wouldn't be right

2237
02:06:08,561 --> 02:06:11,480
for me to ask
the two eldest
to take my name.

2238
02:06:12,315 --> 02:06:17,069
But the little one,
the one who has never
looked on her father,

2239
02:06:17,153 --> 02:06:20,572
could you be thinkin'
of lettin' me
legally adopt her?

2240
02:06:23,284 --> 02:06:28,038
If that time comes,
the child shall
have your name.

2241
02:06:31,918 --> 02:06:34,878
And now I'm wonderin'
if I could smoke my pipe.

2242
02:06:36,714 --> 02:06:38,840
You could have smoked
anytime, Mr. McShane.

2243
02:06:40,385 --> 02:06:43,887
Well, I didn't want
to take any privileges
before I was entitled to 'em.

2244
02:06:48,768 --> 02:06:50,185
Help me put her
to bed, Neeley.

2245
02:06:50,270 --> 02:06:51,478
Why?

2246
02:06:51,562 --> 02:06:53,021
To fix the blankets.

2247
02:07:02,407 --> 02:07:04,866
I'll be heatin' up
the coffee now.

2248
02:07:08,079 --> 02:07:11,039
Will ya join me in a cup,
Mr. McShane?

2249
02:07:12,000 --> 02:07:14,376
Thank you, Katherine.
I will.

2250
02:07:17,046 --> 02:07:18,880
Annie Laurie McShane.

2251
02:07:20,049 --> 02:07:21,216
Yeah.

2252
02:07:21,301 --> 02:07:23,969
She'll never have
the hard times
we had, will she?

2253
02:07:24,053 --> 02:07:26,430
She'll never have
the fun, either.

2254
02:07:27,265 --> 02:07:29,975
We did have fun
when we were young,
didn't we?

2255
02:07:30,059 --> 02:07:31,184
Yeah.

2256
02:07:31,769 --> 02:07:34,187
Remember the olden days
when we collected junk?

2257
02:07:34,397 --> 02:07:35,814
Poor Laurie.

2258
02:07:36,399 --> 02:07:38,942
Neeley,
look at the tree.

2259
02:07:40,278 --> 02:07:43,363
It's growing again,
just like Papa said.

2260
02:07:45,116 --> 02:07:49,870
I feel kind of sad,
like we're saying
goodbye to something.

2261
02:07:49,954 --> 02:07:51,079
Yeah.

2262
02:07:53,791 --> 02:07:55,334
Neeley?
Mmm-hmm?

2263
02:07:57,503 --> 02:07:58,628
Am I good-looking?

2264
02:07:58,713 --> 02:08:00,213
What's eatin' ya?

2265
02:08:00,298 --> 02:08:02,632
No, honest, Neeley.
I wanna know.

2266
02:08:08,014 --> 02:08:09,431
You'll pass.

2267
02:08:10,725 --> 02:08:12,059
You're sweet, Neeley.

2268
02:08:12,143 --> 02:08:13,602
Oh, cut the mush.


